s East and Vis Vienna, many team members asked me how many people were in the CUHK team and I replied 12, and many gave me the response that our team was a big one. Thinking back, this is exactly what Peter wanted - to teach, influence and touch as many students’ lives as possible with the life-changing Vis Moot experience. \r\n\r\nThank you Peter, for giving me such a precious once-in-a-lifetime opportunity in law school of being a part of the Vis Family. Vis Moot has been the highlight of my law school life. When I reminisce the time I had at CUHK Law School, Vis Moot definitely comes first in my mind (in addition to the Sachertorte that Peter and Connie treated the Vis team in Vienna). \r\n\r\nWhen we met up for the 10th Vis Family reunion approximately ten years ago (?) which took place in a Chinese restaurant, Peter came to me to ask how I was doing. I told him that I missed Connie''s carrot cake the most about Vis. You can see his face lit up with joy saying that this was very sweet of me to say so and that no one has said this first thing to him. You can tell that he was very touched and can totally see the love he had for Connie. \r\n\r\nOutside of Vis, he is the best professor I have ever met - he makes tort law so memorable and fun for freshers, making every detail so relatable. Peter’s lectures are still vivid in my mind - he mentioned details of tort law cases such as Harland & Wolff is the company that built the Titanic, his favourite phrases such as "justice demands!" (saying it while pointing his index finger) and "deep pockets" (saying it while patting his own trousers pockets), always starting off tort tutorials with the news of the day etc., making tort so relatable to our daily lives.\r\n\r\nPeter will be missed. He is irreplaceable. His legacy will remain. The seeds of knowledge that he planted will grow forever. \r\n\r\nStephanie Poon (CUHK LLB Class of 2015, Vis Team 2012-2013)','\r',char(13)),'\n',char(10)),'/api/images/tribute-1752947467365-c7xocei70.jpeg','scypoon@hotmail.com','+85297467023',1,'2025-07-19 17:51:08','2025-07-20T00:02:11.707Z',NULL);
INSERT INTO "tributes" ("id","name","message","image_url","email","phone","approved","created_at","approved_at","admin_notes") VALUES(18,'Howard & Darian Libauer','We were instant friends with Peter since late 1984, when we found ourselves in the same RNR unit in Hong Kong.  Peter’s passing leaves a big void in our lives, as it most certainly does with many other people who came to Peter for professional guidance.  We were charmed by his quiet demeanour as well as his generosity and sense of humor.  His range of personal interests was immense and he never failed to bring new perspectives to the table.  He will be badly missed.',NULL,NULL,NULL,1,'2025-07-20 02:13:39','2025-07-20T02:58:14.674Z',NULL);
INSERT INTO "tributes" ("id","name","message","image_url","email","phone","approved","created_at","approved_at","admin_notes") VALUES(19,'Anonymous',replace(replace('[This is a request for correction of a previous post.]\r\n\r\nIn the previous post "Tort might not be my best subject, but Peter was the best teacher. The attached photo was taken on 3 April 2024 at the end of the last lecture of the Tort 2 course at CUHK.", I typed the year incorrectly. The year should be 3 April 2014 not 2024. My apologies. \r\n\r\nI''m going to re-submit a post with the corrected date. You can either (A) amend the old one and ignore the new one; or (B) delete the old one and replace it with the new one. ','\r',char(13)),'\n',char(10)),NULL,NULL,NULL,0,'2025-07-20 05:31:23',NULL,NULL);
INSERT INTO "tributes" ("id","name","message","image_url","email","phone","approved","created_at","approved_at","admin_notes") VALUES(20,'Anonymous','Tort might not be my best subject, but Peter was the best teacher. The attached photo was taken on 3 April 2014 at the end of the last lecture of the Tort 2 course at CUHK.','/api/images/tribute-1752989519387-onbhwmu0d.jpeg',NULL,NULL,1,'2025-07-20 05:32:00','2025-07-20T14:43:36.807Z',NULL);
INSERT INTO "tributes" ("id","name","message","image_url","email","phone","approved","created_at","approved_at","admin_notes") VALUES(21,'Yan Jiabing','Peter was a healthy, inspiring, and positive figure for all CUHK law students. I vividly remember how he would always arrive for our early tort law classes, fresh from his uphill walk, with a towel around his neck and a warm smile. That energy, embodied in a senior professor, invigorated every student in the room–an energy that will continue to inspire us long after graduation. He will always be remembered as a passionate mentor by all who had the privilege to learn from him.',NULL,NULL,NULL,1,'2025-07-20 06:29:58','2025-07-20T14:43:33.638Z',NULL);
INSERT INTO "tributes" ("id","name","message","image_url","email","phone","approved","created_at","approved_at","admin_notes") VALUES(22,'Derek and Angela Cowley','Peter was a dear friend, a true gentleman. We will always remember his kindness,  generosity and his humour. We were fortunate to spend some time with him and Connie in Hong Kong in 2018. We had such fun together. We’ll always remember him. Condolences to family,  friends and colleagues. ','/api/images/tribute-1752993373779-ckz31xedh.jpeg','cowleyangela@hotmail.com',NULL,1,'2025-07-20 06:36:15','2025-07-20T14:43:29.742Z',NULL);
INSERT INTO "tributes" ("id","name","message","image_url","email","phone","approved","created_at","approved_at","admin_notes") VALUES(23,'Paul Mitchard','It was so sad for me to hear of Peter’s passing. Over ten years, during my time at CUHK Law, he was a good friend and supporter of my project as well as a fellow rugby enthusiast with whom I spent many morning breaks discussing the sport.  We worked together with the Vis Moot teams throughout this time, something which Peter pursued with a passion and for which numerous students will be forever grateful as they learned advocacy skills which for many will further their career ambitions. It is difficult to imagine a more modest and self-effacing person to have had as a colleague and friend. We will all miss you, Peter, rest in peace.',NULL,'pmitchard@aol.com','+447946609777',1,'2025-07-20 08:56:45','2025-07-20T14:43:26.934Z',NULL);
INSERT INTO "tributes" ("id","name","message","image_url","email","phone","approved","created_at","approved_at","admin_notes") VALUES(24,'Jean Lau',replace(replace('I’m deeply saddened by the passing of Prof. Peter Rhodes. Being part of the CUHK Vis Moot team in 2010, with Peter as our coach, was truly one of the highlights of my time in CUHK law school. He believed in us, pushed us to be better advocates, and gave us the confidence to compete on the international stage. I’ll never forget the evening gatherings at his home and our time in Vienna - filled with warmth, laughter, and the kind of mentorship that went far beyond mooting. Peter didn’t just teach us how to argue a case, he showed us what it meant to care deeply about the people you guide. \r\n\r\nThank you, Peter, for everything. You will always be remembered with love and gratitude.','\r',char(13)),'\n',char(10)),NULL,'lcyjean@gmail.com',NULL,1,'2025-07-20 09:07:32','2025-07-20T14:43:22.116Z',NULL);
INSERT INTO "tributes" ("id","name","message","image_url","email","phone","approved","created_at","approved_at","admin_notes") VALUES(25,'Bonnie Ng',replace(replace('With heartfelt sorrow, I write in remembrance of Professor Peter Rhodes - our beloved professor, mentor, and friend. \r\n\r\nPeter was a lifelong teacher. His passion for teaching is encapsulated in the pages of our textbooks, and echoed in the quiet depths of our knowledge. He recognised the potential in every student, and held trust in anyone with a positive attitude to learn. I had once asked Peter why our university had gathered a big team of twelve for the Vis moot competition, his reply being a firm belief that mooting was an opportunity for students to learn, an opportunity he wished to extend to as many students as possible, which he had done so with great success. \r\n\r\nPeter was always the life of the party. The first to hop in a go-kart, to introduce everyone to his acclaimed drink of choice, the Almdudler, the social butterfly who has built a network of friendships with other schools within the Vis Moot competition. Going anywhere in Vienna with the familiarity of our group being greeted with “hey Peter” made us feel right at home. Most importantly, Peter was our biggest advocate. He was forgiving, and had never faulted any students which held true to his belief of a fair chance for people to learn and grow. Above all he believed in us. He believed in us than we could in ourselves and impressed upon us values of patience, resilience and empathy. Like a proud father who celebrated our milestones, the captioned picture was at my graduation photo day, shortly after Peter held up his phone to say with excitement, “Bonnie, Atta, smile!”.\r\n\r\nThank you, Peter. I will always be grateful the gift of a lifelong mentor and friend whose legacy will for years live on, as the giant whose shoulders we will all continue to stand on. ','\r',char(13)),'\n',char(10)),'/api/images/tribute-1753009252906-5lcjtzokq.png','bonnieng18@gmail.com','+852 56223171',1,'2025-07-20 11:00:53','2025-07-20T14:43:19.476Z',NULL);
INSERT INTO "tributes" ("id","name","message","image_url","email","phone","approved","created_at","approved_at","admin_notes") VALUES(26,'Anonymous','Peter was the best law teacher who always conducted his lessons with passion and enthusiasm. I am so grateful to have spent 13 weeks of tort lessons with Peter and it’s undoubtedly the most incredible experience I’ve had with my law school journey. Rest well Peter!','/api/images/tribute-1753021713267-v0a2zlg26.jpeg',NULL,NULL,1,'2025-07-20 14:28:35','2025-07-20T14:43:15.883Z',NULL);
INSERT INTO "tributes" ("id","name","message","image_url","email","phone","approved","created_at","approved_at","admin_notes") VALUES(27,'JEFFREY CHAN WAH TECK, SC','Peter was a dear, trusted and reliable friend. He and Connie were among the first persons we met in Harvard in 1983 where we found that we had so many commonalities and were able to speak to each other in the same language at the same level. Peter then was Dean of HKU Law School and thus commanded enhanced respect among our classmates. Also his area of study, international commercial arbitration, which was then a new area generated much interested in me and other students in our class. We developed a close relationship with Peter and Connie, visiting them in their lovely home in Back Bay, Boston,  and they visiting us in our tiny apartment in Peabody Terrace. A memorable event was when Peter and I, together with his host student Mike Lyon, went on a day trip to Newport Rhode Island to see the mansions there and also to gawk at the yachts of the America Cup race. Peter was a sailor and also then in the Canadian Naval Reserve. That was my first trip out of Boston. We continued our close relationship well after we left Harvard. We never failed to visit Peter and Connie and have a meal with them each time we were in HK while they never failed to meet up with us for at least a meal whenever they visited in Singapore. A particularly memorable occasion was when they visited us together with Connie''s parents when they were on a driving holiday to West Malaysia. On one occasion when I was in HK, I invited Peter as my guest to a lunch meeting of the Rotary Club of Peninsula Kowloon where he received a very warm welcome from some of the members who turned out to be former students of his. Peter and I kept track of each other''s careers and I followed with interest the steady progress of Peter''s professional career in academia, in training and knowledge management in law firms, and then back to academia. One common interest we had was the Vis Moots where I had a special interest, being a previous Chairman of UNCITRAL. Peter was the coach of the CHKU Vis Moot teams for many years, training them as well as leading them to Vienna for the Moots. Given our close relationship, Peter and I shared many things about our careers, our views of the world and our family. We trusted each other innately. As both of us approached retirement we began sharing plans about retirement. My last visit to HK was in  March 2025 where I spent an evening with Peter and Connie with dinner at the Wu Kong restaurant followed by a walk to view the spectacular Kowloon waterfront. Connie snapped the last photo I had with Peter - taken at the Peninsula Hotel (see attached) . His last words to me was that he will be coming to visit us in Singapore after his retirement. The news we received from Connie about his passing was a thunderbolt to us. We were stunned and could not react. We had lost a close and good friend and one who through his friendship and sharing had enriched our lives, notwithstanding the distance between Singapore and HK. Our deepest condolences to Connie, Graham and Jean on this loss. We join them in their grief over the passing of a friend who meant so much to us and who, through his friendship and sharing, had shaped and enriched our lives. Farewell my dear friend....','/api/images/tribute-1753023162638-l10vm6c7t.jpeg','jchan.8882@gmail.com','96444807',1,'2025-07-20 14:52:43','2025-07-20T16:03:13.049Z',NULL);
INSERT INTO "tributes" ("id","name","message","image_url","email","phone","approved","created_at","approved_at","admin_notes") VALUES(28,'Peter MacKinnon','My wife Janice and I were friends of Peter and Connie in Canada, and from across the Pacific after they moved to Hong Kong.  Other memories shared in this tribute resonate with us. Peter was a great educator, an outstanding colleague, a wise and temperate voice in collegial and other matters, a warm and trusted advisor, and a dear friend. A very fine man has left this world, but remains in our hearts.',NULL,'rpetermackinnon@gmail.com','(403) 493-1232 ',1,'2025-07-20 15:29:44','2025-07-20T16:03:10.566Z',NULL);
INSERT INTO "tributes" ("id","name","message","image_url","email","phone","approved","created_at","approved_at","admin_notes") VALUES(29,'Andrew Coggins Jr','Today I grieve the loss of a dear friend. I first met Peter on the CUHK Campus Shuttle in 2006 and we became fast friends. Aside from the joy of seeing Peter and Connie, my fondest CUHK memories of Peter are seeing him having his morning coffee on his balcony as I was walking up the hill from my morning walk. After I left CUHK in 2010, Hong Kong was always on my itinerary when I visited Asia and my dinners with Peter and Connie were the high points of the trip! May Peter rest in peace and God comfort Connie, Graham, Jean, and their family ad friends!',NULL,'acoggins@pace.edu','9144792068',1,'2025-07-20 17:36:29','2025-07-20T17:47:22.394Z',NULL);
INSERT INTO "tributes" ("id","name","message","image_url","email","phone","approved","created_at","approved_at","admin_notes") VALUES(30,'Clare Vickers','Peter and Connie were almost the first people we met when we arrived in Hong Kong in 1979.  They were great travellers and we had many a dinner in one of the many restaurants in and around the territory exchanging stories and opinions on everything under the sun.  I last saw Peter in 2003 which is a world away now, but we always kept in touch.  My heart goes out to Connie, Graham and Jean and their families. He will be sorely missed.',NULL,'claryvickers@hotmail.com','07736706372',1,'2025-07-20 17:42:42','2025-07-20T17:47:21.211Z',NULL);
INSERT INTO "tributes" ("id","name","message","image_url","email","phone","approved","created_at","approved_at","admin_notes") VALUES(31,'Norman & Catherine Ford',replace(replace('Dear All,\r\n\r\nIt was with tremendous shock and great sadness that we learned of the most premature passing of our best friend Peter whilst just starting to enjoy his retirement with a safari in Tanzania in East Africa. Words will never express how sad we feel.\r\n\r\nWe have known Peter and Connie since the late 80’s in Hong Kong where Peter, Connie, ourselves and other friends met almost every week after work out activities. They were really most fun people to be with.\r\n\r\nWe moved to Canada in 2000 but always kept in touch through annual visits to Hong Kong. Peter would always take us on a walk which ended at an excellent eatery which they had discovered. Our last visit was in April / May 2024 during which they both looked after us so well despite the fact that Connie was departing on a Spanish walking tour the next day.\r\n\r\nI have had cancer since 2019 but Peter has always been so supportive in that EVERY e-mail ended with the words “Stay Strong”, which I am doing. I will remember this encouragement for ever as I will remember Peter.\r\n\r\nI am a retired ship’s Captain and Peter sent me the attached photos of his early student days working a transit across the Pacific (which was allowed in these days).\r\n\r\nThe World has just lost an amazing person with so much more to contribute in retirement. Our thoughts are with Connie, Jean and Graham and all the family.','\r',char(13)),'\n',char(10)),'/api/images/tribute-1753059130285-p80yr1w50.jpeg','Norman.Ford@telus.net','604-421-6925',1,'2025-07-21 00:52:10','2025-07-21T01:20:28.806Z',NULL);
INSERT INTO "tributes" ("id","name","message","image_url","email","phone","approved","created_at","approved_at","admin_notes") VALUES(32,'J. Rhodes',replace(replace('[2/4] Please kindly refer to a message from Norman and Catherine Ford.  \r\n\r\nFor background, these photos were taken in late November 1968 (after Peter''s third year of law school) on one of his famous adventures.  He worked his way on a ship called the Cap Finisterre from New Zealand to Canada as part of a scheme known as a "Workaway Passage."   This ship was owned by the Columbus Line a subsidiary of a German shipping company Hamburg Sud. Peter was not paid, but in exchange for his work he got a free passage on the ship to Canada.   \r\n\r\nFrom Vancouver he travelled across Canada, the USA and Mexico on a Greyhound bus pass – US$99 for 99 days of bus travel.  Peter spent one night in a roadside inn for every two on the bus.  He ended the bus trip in San Francisco in late February 1969 and thereafter flew to Hawaii and caught a ship back to Auckland (as a passenger) arriving in early March 1969 just in time to start his fourth year of law school.\r\n\r\nPeter was assigned the job of engine room cleaner (Reiniger). In these photos you can see him on deck getting some fresh air and cleaning up a bit after his efforts in a rather dirty engine room.  A further photo shows some of his first experiences of the extreme North American weather.  One example of his intrepid spirit and endless wonder and interest in the wider world around him.','\r',char(13)),'\n',char(10)),'/api/images/tribute-1753061624819-1wq0dwroa.jpeg',NULL,NULL,1,'2025-07-21 01:33:46','2025-07-21T01:36:32.611Z',NULL);
INSERT INTO "tributes" ("id","name","message","image_url","email","phone","approved","created_at","approved_at","admin_notes") VALUES(33,'J. Rhodes','[3/4] Please kindly refer to an earlier message from Norman and Catherine Ford.','/api/images/tribute-1753061713054-cj4l6q80q.jpeg',NULL,NULL,1,'2025-07-21 01:35:14','2025-07-21T01:36:34.749Z',NULL);
INSERT INTO "tributes" ("id","name","message","image_url","email","phone","approved","created_at","approved_at","admin_notes") VALUES(34,'J. Rhodes','[4/4] Please kindly refer to an earlier message from Norman and Catherine Ford.','/api/images/tribute-1753061773891-fqwgpaxah.jpeg',NULL,NULL,1,'2025-07-21 01:36:15','2025-07-21T01:36:38.854Z',NULL);
INSERT INTO "tributes" ("id","name","message","image_url","email","phone","approved","created_at","approved_at","admin_notes") VALUES(35,'Philippa Howcroft','It was very sad to hear of Peters passing, he was such a kind and thoughtful person, very clever of course but he never came at things from the point of knowing everything but was curious and interested in all kinds of areas.  He loved to travel and went to lots of fascinating destinations and made the most of every single one, travelling not just to holiday but to enjoy and experience the world and all the people in it. He seemed to enjoy teaching enormously and was often working extra hours helping students and preparing for the Mout (i''m not sure of exactly how to spell this) which required lots of planning and preparation. He will be sadly missed not only by his family but I''m sure by the staff and students of the university.  Our family will most certainly miss him and Hong Kong wont be the same without hime.',NULL,'howpip@gmail.com','0210708934',1,'2025-07-21 02:16:12','2025-07-21T03:35:40.829Z',NULL);
INSERT INTO "tributes" ("id","name","message","image_url","email","phone","approved","created_at","approved_at","admin_notes") VALUES(36,'SHIU, LIK KING','Your passions in the Vis Moot and teaching Tort Law shall not be forgotten.  Thank you.',NULL,'lk.i.unlimited@gmail.com',NULL,1,'2025-07-21 08:22:22','2025-07-21T11:44:00.584Z',NULL);
INSERT INTO "tributes" ("id","name","message","image_url","email","phone","approved","created_at","approved_at","admin_notes") VALUES(37,'Maciej Durbas',replace(replace('It is with a heavy heart that I share the passing of Peter Rhodes, an exceptional academic, dedicated lawyer, and veteran Vis Moot coach who touched the lives of countless individuals throughout his career.\r\nI had the privilege of knowing Peter for many years, beginning with our first meeting during my participation in the Willem C. Vis International Commercial Arbitration Moot. What began as a professional connection through our shared passion for international arbitration evolved into a friendship spanning continents.\r\nPeter was a cornerstone of the Vis Moot community, serving as the long-standing coach of the Chinese University of Hong Kong team. His dedication to mentoring the next generation of international arbitration practitioners was truly remarkable. CUHK teams always had more than 10 participants. Thus, Peter had to mentor hundreds of young lawyers. \r\nDuring my LL.M. studies in Hong Kong, I was fortunate to spend considerable time with Peter, deepening our friendship and learning from his vast expertise.\r\nWhat set Peter apart was not only his legal and academic skills but his extraordinary intellectual curiosity. Our discussions and email exchanges were a constant source of inspiration. His knowledge of global politics and history was encyclopedic. I was continually amazed by his deep understanding of Polish history and culture, often surpassing what one might expect from anyone, let alone someone from outside Poland. I learned a lot from him, e.g., about Polish children evacuated from the USSR to New Zealand (where Peter was born) in 1944. \r\nOne of my most treasured memories was when Peter visited Poland and Kraków. My family and I were delighted to welcome him and his wife, Connie, for a traditional Polish Easter breakfast, a moment that perfectly captured his warmth and genuine interest in connecting with different cultures and traditions.\r\nThe international arbitration community has lost not just a brilliant legal mind, but a mentor, friend, and bridge-builder. Peter will be missed. My thoughts are with his family. \r\n','\r',char(13)),'\n',char(10)),NULL,'maciej.durbas@kkg.pl',NULL,1,'2025-07-21 11:39:11','2025-07-21T11:44:20.127Z',NULL);
INSERT INTO "tributes" ("id","name","message","image_url","email","phone","approved","created_at","approved_at","admin_notes") VALUES(38,'Louise Parsons','It is with great sadness that I heard of the passing of Peter. Peter was a true friend and colleague. Our association has spanned 15 years of the Vis Moot competition with Peter as the coach of the CUHK team, and me as the coach of the Bond University team. Although I am in Australia and Peter was in Hong Kong, we coordinated our practices with the teams, and the annual CUHK/Bond premoot became a true ''item'' on the calendar. Past team members would excitedly tell new team members about the CUHK-Bond practice moot and the accompanying socials. I have many fond memories of Bond Vis teams arriving at the train station at the Shatin campus, HK, and then being enthusiastically transported to the Law Faculty for the practice moots in Peter''s car. In Vienna, we mooted in hotels and then took the teams to the Prater. Peter was beloved by the Bond team members, even though he gave them a hard time in the dodge cars! And to share a meal with Peter and his team was always a highlight. In Hong Kong, it sometimes involved some of Connie''s famous chocolate cake. Over the years more than a collaboration developed - we became friends. We shared values in education, and a joint belief in the importance of experiential learning. Peter led his teams with distinction and his great leadership not just in imparting legal knowledge but life skills and social values, resulting in scores of CUHK Vis graduates who are exemplary individuals. Peter demonstrated all the values of a great lawyer and academic. I will miss him greatly. I attach the last photo taken with Peter in Vienna 2025 with his wife Connie and friend and colleague Dr Can Eken of Durham University. You will be sorely missed, Peter. My thoughts are with Connie, his children, students and colleagues, and friends.','/api/images/tribute-1753103622365-ggiz6wt2d.jpeg','lparsons@bond.edu.au',NULL,1,'2025-07-21 13:13:43','2025-07-21T14:46:43.253Z',NULL);
INSERT INTO "tributes" ("id","name","message","image_url","email","phone","approved","created_at","approved_at","admin_notes") VALUES(39,'Savita Verma',replace(replace('The heartbreaking news of Peter''s passing arrived yesterday. I saw Connie and Peter last summer when they were visiting Toronto. They were travelling to far-off and interesting places - as always. And Peter had stories about them all. I first met Connie and Peter in 1978 in Saskatoon. Friendship with them brought introduction to the prairies life, interesting and fun family gatherings, and interesting and informative discussions on issues of little as well as great importance. \r\nConnie: you have always been a strong person and presence of your children with you will, of course,  provide additional much needed support. I will look for the next opportunity to see you in person for a big hug and we will remember Peter together.','\r',char(13)),'\n',char(10)),NULL,NULL,NULL,1,'2025-07-21 14:50:43','2025-07-21T15:40:47.881Z',NULL);
INSERT INTO "tributes" ("id","name","message","image_url","email","phone","approved","created_at","approved_at","admin_notes") VALUES(40,'Cyrus Lee',replace(replace('It was with great shock and sadness that I learned of Peter’s passing. Just a month ago, we celebrated his retirement, where he shared plans for travel around the world.\r\n\r\nOne of his destinations was my hometown, Xi’an. Whenever he spoke of Xi’an, he would tell me about his trip there in the 1990s, where he stood in a long line with hundreds of others for the opening of a restaurant, which, disappointingly, turned out to be the first KFC in Xi’an. \r\n\r\nThis was just one of the many adventures he shared with us. Through his words, he brought us to the River Thames in London, hiking trails in Southern France, and villages with no name in the middle of India. \r\n\r\nOf these journeys, the Vis journey occupied a significant part. For 18 years, Peter served as the head coach of the CUHK Vis moot team. This was a demanding job with little benefit to a professor’s career, and yet Peter embraced it with enthusiasm and joy. He called us the “Vis Family” and treated us as such. It was his loving, selfless heart that drove him year after year to guide and support us.\r\n\r\nI am deeply grateful for Peter’s trust and support throughout and beyond my own Vis journey. He chose me for the team, then as an oralist, despite my flaws and the doubts that surrounded me. I still remember him speaking to me, days before the competition, in his usual gentle and slow voice. He said, “No matter what others say, you have my full confidence. I think the team needs you.” But with a twinkle in his eye, he added, “Except you should stop ignoring the 5-minutes-before-each-meeting rule. It seems to me that you have an attitude problem.”\r\n\r\nUnder Peter’s guidance, the Vis moot was the best thing that happened to me in my law school years. Earlier this year, I invited him to my admission ceremony to the Hong Kong Bar, a moment I was so proud to share with him. The photo we took that day is now one of my most cherished memories.\r\n\r\nPeter’s life was defined by countless journeys. Although his final journey has come to an end, he will live on in the hearts of all who had the privilege of knowing him. His kindness, wisdom, and unwavering belief in others leave a legacy that will never be forgotten.','\r',char(13)),'\n',char(10)),'/api/images/tribute-1753113324022-o895n1id0.jpeg','cyrus.lky@outlook.com','55368473',1,'2025-07-21 15:55:25','2025-07-21T16:58:21.385Z',NULL);
INSERT INTO "tributes" ("id","name","message","image_url","email","phone","approved","created_at","approved_at","admin_notes") VALUES(41,'Anonymous',replace(replace('I met Peter at CUHK. He was my coach and mentor. \r\n\r\nPeter brought me on an experience that has shaped my passion and my career. Like generations of other students taught by him, I stood on Peter’s shoulders - the shoulders of a true giant - and from there, I saw a path of worldly pursuits, formidable challenges and extraordinary opportunities. He showed me what was possible, pushed me to be my very best, and set me on a journey of a lifetime. I am forever grateful. \r\n\r\nI will remember Peter. ','\r',char(13)),'\n',char(10)),NULL,NULL,NULL,1,'2025-07-21 20:51:46','2025-07-21T23:24:31.490Z',NULL);
INSERT INTO "tributes" ("id","name","message","image_url","email","phone","approved","created_at","approved_at","admin_notes") VALUES(42,'Till Rau (born Maier-Lohmann)',replace(replace('During my year abroad at CUHK, I had the privilege of coaching the Vis Moot team alongside Professor Peter Rhodes and three fellow student coaches. During that time, I came to know not only a brilliant legal mind and patient mentor, but someone who genuinely cared about the growth and well-being of those around him. Peter never dictated legal solutions to his students, even though he easily could have. Instead, he believed in drawing out the potential in each of his students. He challenged and encouraged, guided with patience, and led by example. \r\n\r\nBeyond the university, he opened up Hong Kong to me in ways I never could have experienced on my own. He introduced me to local life, culture, and perspective that even a full decade abroad might not have revealed without his insight. Whether hiking together on the MacLehose Trail, which he and his wife Connie lovingly introduced me to, or inviting me to dinner, he gave me more than academic guidance. Peter gave me a deeper connection to a place that has become very special to me because of him.\r\n\r\nWhen my now-wife visited during that year, and college rules prevented her from staying in my dorm, he and Connie treated us like family - warm, generous, and with the quiet kindness that defined so much of his character. I will never forget the occasions we met afterwards in Vienna, sharing Schweinshaxe at the Schweizer Haus, or breakfast at Café Central, often together with Connie. He always took great care to keep in touch, writing e-mails and to videocall. Peter left a lasting mark on me, as he did on so many others. \r\n\r\n"You are standing on the shoulders of giants," he used to say. And indeed, we were, and always will be, standing on his.','\r',char(13)),'\n',char(10)),NULL,'till.rau@outlook.de',NULL,1,'2025-07-21 21:46:48','2025-07-21T23:24:46.307Z',NULL);
INSERT INTO "tributes" ("id","name","message","image_url","email","phone","approved","created_at","approved_at","admin_notes") VALUES(43,'Molly LI',replace(replace('I was shocked by the news, and soon the shock turned into great sorrow. Just in June, we celebrated Peter’s retirement, when Peter looked as strong and energetic as always.\r\n\r\nOur Vis Moot journey just ended in April this year, and it was the best experience in my law school years. It was a great privilege to hear Peter’s passionate introduction to the history of Vienna. Peter trusted every one of his students and I would be forever grateful that he gave me an opportunity to go beyond the limits I set for myself. Before every round, Peter would give a speech about the Vis family’s success, pat me on the shoulder, and then tell me firmly that I could do it as well. I believe that every time I lack confidence in the future, I will recall this moment and cheer myself up.\r\n\r\nThank you, Peter. You will be missed. ','\r',char(13)),'\n',char(10)),NULL,'jiayangli2026@gmail.com','93572702',1,'2025-07-22 04:19:18','2025-07-22T09:28:07.622Z',NULL);
INSERT INTO "tributes" ("id","name","message","image_url","email","phone","approved","created_at","approved_at","admin_notes") VALUES(44,'Toni Chan',replace(replace('Rarely in life do we encounter someone who consistently and tirelessly brings goodness to everyone around them throughout their lives. Peter epitomizes such a never-failing, reliable, honorable, and respectable figure to me. \r\n\r\nSince day one Peter took me under his wing in Vis, he has never ceased to inspire me by his work ethic, intellectual mind, fearless and generous spirit to enjoy life. He has laid such deep foundation for me, and opened so many doors to lead me into the world. Without him, I would simply remain that timid and shy student who had been filled with self-doubt and fear. \r\n\r\nPeter always reminded his students that ''We stand on the shoulders of giants.'' He will always remain one of the greatest giants in my life. A person does not truly die until he has been forgotten – Peter will live on. \r\n','\r',char(13)),'\n',char(10)),'/api/images/tribute-1753163723194-42wbuv1rt.jpeg','toni.cyt@outlook.com',NULL,1,'2025-07-22 05:55:25','2025-07-22T09:28:33.101Z',NULL);
INSERT INTO "tributes" ("id","name","message","image_url","email","phone","approved","created_at","approved_at","admin_notes") VALUES(45,'Michael  Osbourne','Peter was a family friend of my father, Brian, for 60 years.  He was always a wonderful host to my father on visits to Hong Kong and a keen fellow traveller on Peter''s trips to the UK.  The relationship they maintained over decades was more akin to family than friendship - truly special. Peter was a truly special person and I want to say thank you for everything on behalf of my father and my whole family.  You will be deeply missed and your memory cherished.',NULL,'michaelosbourne@btinternet.com','+44 07787515223',1,'2025-07-22 09:28:54','2025-07-22T10:11:53.430Z',NULL);
INSERT INTO "tributes" ("id","name","message","image_url","email","phone","approved","created_at","approved_at","admin_notes") VALUES(46,'Raluca Papadima',replace(replace('Like many others, I''ve met Peter through the Vis moot, 10 years ago. He was the coach of the CUHK team, I was the coach of the University of Bucharest team. Our teams practiced together every year and this practice was one of the highlights for the Romanian students (we are going up against CUHK!). During the online practice sessions, which were generally taking place at crazy times due to the time difference, he would always take a moment to call Connie to say hello. I was fortunate to share a meal with Peter and Connie many times, whether in Hong Kong, Vienna or Bucharest. We''d talk about best practices for coaching and pretty much everything else under the sun. Through Peter''s example, I became a better coach. Through Connie''s support, I became a stronger mother. Peter, I will miss you tremendously. Connie, stay strong and I cannot wait to see you again. I am enclosing the picture we took in 2024 for our lunch in Hong Kong.\r\n\r\n','\r',char(13)),'\n',char(10)),'/api/images/tribute-1753184092083-4dpfnhnae.jpeg','raluca.papadima@gmail.com','+13473260020',1,'2025-07-22 11:34:52','2025-07-22T13:44:16.281Z',NULL);
INSERT INTO "tributes" ("id","name","message","image_url","email","phone","approved","created_at","approved_at","admin_notes") VALUES(47,'J. David Murphy',replace(replace('In 1989 I was a partner with a large international law firm in Toronto, Canada. I''d been successful, but wanted a change.  I answered an ad for a lecturer post at the Faculty of Law, University of Hong Kong. It became apparent that some traditionalists in the Faculty were skeptical about hiring a practitioner from Canada, not an "academic", despite the nature of my litigation practice and the fact that I had been an appellate court law clerk.  However, Peter Rhodes, Dean at the time, had faith in me and I suspect was the main reason I was hired.  This was the start of a very rewarding seven years in Hong Kong and a special friendship with Peter. When I left the firm I worried that I would miss the legal abilities and sophistication of my partners and associates, but this was dispelled when I met Peter. \r\nIn my first few years I was lucky enough to share teaching with Peter on an international trade course. \r\nI have nothing but high regard for Peter''s legal, administrative and personal skills.  I was privileged to call him a special friend.  He encouraged me in my teaching and legal writing.  I think he even supported me when I left to take up a judicial post elsewhere in the world.  He kept in touch, and had useful comments to make on my writings in my local Toronto paper (especially on Hong Kong matters), and on my art exhibitions.\r\n I will pass on one anecdote.  Peter was an adventurous traveller.  One summer I convinced him to come to Canada and do a trail ride on horseback through the Rockies in Alberta. (Picture of us attached)  Not surprisingly he became an instant expert and was praised by the cowboys and guides.  I vividly remember one night in a cabin in the Rockies, in the middle of nowhere, Peter taking on all comers at Trivial Pursuit, and beating us all handily.  That was Peter.\r\n My condolences to Connie and all the family.\r\n David','\r',char(13)),'\n',char(10)),'/api/images/tribute-1753193016837-0ydfi3921.jpeg','jdmgozo@yahoo.ca','1 705 7922911',1,'2025-07-22 14:03:37','2025-07-22T14:13:24.421Z',NULL);
INSERT INTO "tributes" ("id","name","message","image_url","email","phone","approved","created_at","approved_at","admin_notes") VALUES(48,'Bakr Rabie',replace(replace('In Memory of Peter\r\nIt is difficult to put into words the deep sense of loss I feel at Peter’s passing. He was a colleague, a running companion, and, above all, a dear friend.\r\nI first came to know Peter during his time at HKU. From the beginning, I was struck by his humility, sharp intellect, and quiet sense of humour. I was touched by his genuine interest in people and the world, as well as his rare ability to truly listen and care. Whether we were at work or simply running up and down the trails of Hong Kong Island, Peter’s presence always made a difference.\r\nI must share Peter’s excitement when he, Cathay Chan, and I ran the Mizuno Hong Kong Half Marathon. We trained, strategised, and motivated each other throughout. Peter took the lead in planning our training schedule, gradually increasing both our distance and elevation—knowing we’d be facing some tough hills, he wanted us to be well prepared. Peter was a goal-oriented runner, and our collective aim was to finish in under 2 hours and 20 minutes. We did: Peter finished in 2 hours, 17 minutes, and 55 seconds; Cathay and I finished just seconds later. The excitement and sense of achievement Peter felt shone through at every gathering for months afterward.\r\nPeter brought thoughtfulness and calm to every interaction. Conversations with him always left you with new perspectives on life.\r\nPeter’s passing is a profound loss to the entire legal academic community, and to everyone who had the good fortune to know him. His legacy lives on—not only through the countless students he inspired and mentored, but also in the kindness, integrity, and quiet resilience he demonstrated every day.','\r',char(13)),'\n',char(10)),NULL,'bkrabie@gmail.com',NULL,1,'2025-07-22 14:09:58','2025-07-22T14:13:27.342Z',NULL);
INSERT INTO "tributes" ("id","name","message","image_url","email","phone","approved","created_at","approved_at","admin_notes") VALUES(49,'Philip Yue','Peter, you are sorely missed. I have such fond memories of you teaching me Tort Law. You had a way of making even the most complex concepts seem easy to understand. You are strict, but fair, a gentle giant. You did your best to ensure that we all had an equal opportunity to learn. You were always supportive of your students.','/api/images/tribute-1753216655601-3fc2v9dfw.jpeg','philip@philipyue.com',NULL,1,'2025-07-22 20:37:36','2025-07-23T02:31:27.108Z',NULL);
INSERT INTO "tributes" ("id","name","message","image_url","email","phone","approved","created_at","approved_at","admin_notes") VALUES(50,'Grace Humphries',replace(replace('I’ve known Peter and Connie since I was young, as Jean was my best friend when we were small in HK. Over the years, they have been welcoming, warm, and invariably lovely company across any number of meetings and encounters. I’ve enjoyed seeing them anywhere from California during pride parade to back in HK, where Peter and Connie were generous and thoughtful hosts during my summer stay in their home while teaching English. Connie and Peter showed me new sights, recommended activities, and took me shopping. I had a truly wonderful and bustling stay in HK, in no small part due to them - it was a formative experience of the city for me, years after growing up there. Peter introduced me to my summer social circle, ensuring that I, as someone who hadn’t lived in HK in a while, had a community and friends. I remember watching a film about young princess Victoria with Peter - I don’t recall the detail of our exchanges but I have such a strong sense of it being a much needed calming and contented evening in. \r\n\r\nIn recent years, I have seen Peter and Connie with my parents - they brought with them engaging conversation, sincere insights and wry humour - spanning anything from politics to culture. Looking back and reflecting now, both Peter and Connie have been a model of true partnership, not only with one another, but in the way they could so naturally bring in friends, old and new, to feel like one of the family. ','\r',char(13)),'\n',char(10)),NULL,NULL,NULL,1,'2025-07-22 20:44:03','2025-07-23T02:31:36.793Z',NULL);
INSERT INTO "tributes" ("id","name","message","image_url","email","phone","approved","created_at","approved_at","admin_notes") VALUES(51,'brian baillie',replace(replace('I met Peter when I joined the Law GFaculty at the University of Hong Kong in January 1991.  I had come from pracrising as a barrister in Australia. Peter, Dean of the Faculty, as a near "cousin" Kiwi was most welcoming and helpful. He was , throuigh out me 9 years at HKU ( and on occasions I saw him siusbsequently) a genuinely good bloke!  Very sad he has gone.  Sincere condollences to Connie and family.\r\n\r\nBrian Baillie','\r',char(13)),'\n',char(10)),NULL,'brianbaillie@fredkan.com',NULL,1,'2025-07-23 06:23:35','2025-07-23T13:54:56.593Z',NULL);
INSERT INTO "tributes" ("id","name","message","image_url","email","phone","approved","created_at","approved_at","admin_notes") VALUES(52,'Sala Sihombing','Sending much love to Connie and the whole family.  I remember meeting Peter as a little girl when we moved to HK.  We lived nearby and I always remember seeing him run up from Sha Wan Drive to the Peak.  He seemed like a giant to me.  I also had the good fortune to get to know Peter when he wasn''t running, and his warmth and kindness, his intelligence and integrity will stay with me. ',NULL,'hksihombing@gmail.com',NULL,1,'2025-07-23 08:03:45','2025-07-23T13:55:00.121Z',NULL);
INSERT INTO "tributes" ("id","name","message","image_url","email","phone","approved","created_at","approved_at","admin_notes") VALUES(53,'Janny Leung',replace(replace('I knew Peter mostly through hiking and get togethers at Morningside College, CUHK. (The picture is from one of our many hikes.)\r\nPeter had a strong passion for teaching. He always had ideas on what to teach and how to teach so that the learning for students can be more effective. He cared deeply about his students; what is so amazing is that he made the effort to get to know each of them as individuals and provided each of them tailor-made mentoring. The many testimonials from his students attest to how they appreciated Peter. \r\nBeing such a humble person, Peter never said much about his wealth of experiences and his many adventures. I only learned about his many accomplishments through bits and pieces of conversations here and there … and I am still learning about more of his remarkable life now.  He was truly a special person! I am so grateful to have had the opportunity to get to know him. \r\nDeepest condolences to Connie, Graham and Jean.\r\n','\r',char(13)),'\n',char(10)),'/api/images/tribute-1753265010991-ng3p9yxew.jpeg','jannyleung@um.edu.mo','91552295',1,'2025-07-23 10:03:33','2025-07-23T13:55:19.587Z',NULL);
INSERT INTO "tributes" ("id","name","message","image_url","email","phone","approved","created_at","approved_at","admin_notes") VALUES(54,'Judith Sihombing',replace(replace('How sad to lose  a great friend, and a fine man.  Working with Peter was a joy - his integrity always shown through.\r\nI knew Peter and Connie from  my first days in Hong Kong ,  and later Graham and Jeanie.  With much love and deep condolences to the family\r\n','\r',char(13)),'\n',char(10)),NULL,NULL,NULL,1,'2025-07-24 02:41:42','2025-07-24T03:32:10.695Z',NULL);
INSERT INTO "tributes" ("id","name","message","image_url","email","phone","approved","created_at","approved_at","admin_notes") VALUES(55,'Yash Ghai and Jill Cottrell (Ghai)',replace(replace('It was with great sadness that we learned of Peter''s death, at what we would consider a young age.  We offer our sincere condolences to Connie and his friends and family. \r\nPeter was Dean when we arrived in Hong Kong, Yash as the first holder of the Sir Y K Pao Chair in December 1989 and Jill as  lecturer in August 1990. \r\nPeter was always a friendly, warm and efficient colleague and leader of the faculty.  We would whole-heartedly endorse the comments of our former HKU colleagues which are linked on this site. ','\r',char(13)),'\n',char(10)),NULL,'jill.ghai@gmail.com','+254714512391',1,'2025-07-24 07:24:44','2025-07-24T12:50:39.072Z',NULL);
INSERT INTO "tributes" ("id","name","message","image_url","email","phone","approved","created_at","approved_at","admin_notes") VALUES(56,'Colin, Jacqueline, Clive and David Graham',replace(replace('As a family, we were all extremely saddened and shocked by Peter''s sudden death.\r\nHe was a huge part our family life since 2006, and we will all miss him dearly.\r\nOur thoughts go out to Connie, Graham and Jean at this very sad time. ','\r',char(13)),'\n',char(10)),NULL,'jackie@cagraham.com','07482666525',1,'2025-07-24 10:07:47','2025-07-24T12:50:56.716Z',NULL);
INSERT INTO "tributes" ("id","name","message","image_url","email","phone","approved","created_at","approved_at","admin_notes") VALUES(57,'Robert Nield','I knew Peter for 40 years or so, principally through connections with the HKU Law School and through Connie when she and I worked at the same firm - Price Waterhouse in Hong Kong. (I have attached a photo from the PW Annual Dinner in 1989.) He always struck me as solid and dependable, and someone who took a genuine interest - not a bad description of a lawyer by an accountant! Janet and I were lucky enough to see them both and spend some good time together when they visited us in Canada not many months ago. I was very touched that he took such an interest in my own research activities that he brought a book with him that he thought I might find useful. I did. I thanked him at the time, and I do so again. Thank you, Peter.','/api/images/tribute-1753399042061-6wkbn5djs.jpeg',NULL,NULL,1,'2025-07-24 23:17:22','2025-07-24T23:44:36.445Z',NULL);
INSERT INTO "tributes" ("id","name","message","image_url","email","phone","approved","created_at","approved_at","admin_notes") VALUES(58,'Kate Mead',replace(replace('I first met Peter when he came to speak to my students at the Hong Kong Polytechnic University about the significant use of simple, clear language in the legal profession.  His clarity, eloquence and quiet humour was a joy for us all to experience on several special occasions.\r\nAs a result of the university connection, I then came to know Peter and Connie, as near neighbours and fellow hikers. Many an interesting and lively meal would be enjoyed after some energetic hikes. I even had the pleasure to dine with Connie and Peter on a visit to Auckland where we all happened to be at the same time.  It was also an opportunity to meet Peter’s brother.\r\nAs a near neighbour, fellow hiker and good friend of Connie’s, I was so shocked and saddened to hear of Peter’s passing.  One small consolation, Peter was enjoying the delights of exotic travel, something I know he loved.\r\nWe have all lost a fine man, an excellent educator and a great loss to the legal profession.\r\nMy deepest sympathy to Connie, Graham and Jean.\r\nKate Mead','\r',char(13)),'\n',char(10)),'/api/images/tribute-1753414349540-otn1k8w11.jpeg','katemead1@gmail.com','+61 0422421585',1,'2025-07-25 03:32:32','2025-07-25T05:25:01.208Z',NULL);
INSERT INTO "tributes" ("id","name","message","image_url","email","phone","approved","created_at","approved_at","admin_notes") VALUES(59,'Susan Shing',replace(replace('Dear Connie,\r\n\r\nI was so sorry to hear Peter passing. My heart aches for you and your family during this painful time.\r\nI knew Peter and Connie for over 35 years through Stuart. We visited each others so many times in Sydney and HK including 10 years Navy reunion in London.\r\nI will always remember Peter’s incredible warmth, generosity and sense of humour.  Peter touched so many lives and his legacy will live on.\r\nConnie,  you are in my thoughts and I’m sending you strength and love.\r\nWith my deepest sympathy.\r\n\r\nSusan. \r\n','\r',char(13)),'\n',char(10)),NULL,'susanshing@hotmail.com','0410108878',1,'2025-07-25 04:32:51','2025-07-25T05:25:06.840Z',NULL);
INSERT INTO "tributes" ("id","name","message","image_url","email","phone","approved","created_at","approved_at","admin_notes") VALUES(60,'Anonymous',replace(replace('Peter was such a wonderful and passionate teacher who made 9:30am law lectures fun and informative at the same time. Although I didn''t know Peter on a personal level, I couldn''t help feeling hollowed upon learning about Peter''s sudden passing.\r\nRIP Peter, you''ll be terribly missed.','\r',char(13)),'\n',char(10)),NULL,NULL,NULL,1,'2025-07-25 17:14:20','2025-07-26T20:16:46.967Z',NULL);
INSERT INTO "tributes" ("id","name","message","image_url","email","phone","approved","created_at","approved_at","admin_notes") VALUES(61,'Peter Fields','When we go through life we  sometimes meet people who you genuinely and instinctively very much like and admire, Peter was such a person. On learning of  Peter''s untimely passing today I can safely say that it affected all of our family. To say that we were shocked and very saddened would be an under statement. This very sudden news has really numbed us all. Peter, wherever you may be, please rest assured that you were a very special person who influenced many lives  and that your legacy will live for many years to come. For Connie and family please accept our very sincere condolences on the loss of a wonderful husband, father and a genuinely well respected and loved person. Peter, Ladawan and Som Fields. (New Zealand).',NULL,'peladsom@xtra.co.nz','=64 020 414 86785',1,'2025-07-25 17:19:56','2025-07-26T20:16:50.051Z',NULL);
INSERT INTO "tributes" ("id","name","message","image_url","email","phone","approved","created_at","approved_at","admin_notes") VALUES(62,'Karen & Garry Little',replace(replace('Garry and I were so shocked and saddened by Peter’s sudden passing.\r\nWe met Connie, Peter, Graham and Jean when they were part of the St Cuthbert''s College family in New Zealand.\r\nOver the years while in Auckland and then when they moved back to Hong Kong, we had memorable dinners and gatherings together. We were pleased to have had dinner with Peter’s mother, and met his brother on many occasions.\r\nWe all managed to keep in touch via their very informative Christmas emails and frequent trips back to New Zealand.\r\nWe will miss Peter’s gentle charm and inquisitive mind, and his travel stories that  kept us all enthralled.\r\nRest in peace, Peter.\r\n\r\n','\r',char(13)),'\n',char(10)),NULL,'karenfranceslittle56@gmail.com','+6421670871',1,'2025-07-26 02:04:27','2025-07-26T20:16:53.286Z',NULL);
INSERT INTO "tributes" ("id","name","message","image_url","email","phone","approved","created_at","approved_at","admin_notes") VALUES(63,'Ray Johnson',replace(replace('I was very surprised to receive a phone call from Connie while she was on a trip with Peter in Tanzania. I had been talking with Connie numerous times in the past couple months given the passing of my spouse, Eloise, who was a dear friend of Connie and Peter from University years. My surprise quickly turned to shock as I learned of Peter sudden passing and then to sadness realizing the loss for Connie, family, colleagues, and friends.\r\n\r\nIt was comforting to learn they were travelling with supportive friends and arrangements were already in place for Graham and Jean to travel there and assist Connie with preparations and a return home.\r\n\r\nEloise and I had always considered Peter and Connie to be neighbours even though we lived in different countries 20,000 km apart. We shared so many similarities in our families and our thoughts about international affairs. One or both of us had the opportunity to travel with Peter and Connie to China, Singapore, New York, and California. We would often joke about Peter’s meticulous preparations for travel and the days events, but in truth were so appreciative of his detailed planning. I know this same planning went into his teaching and mentorship roles at the college of law and it is so evident in the comments from his colleagues and students.\r\n\r\nPeter will be missed by family, friends, colleagues, students, and neighbors.\r\n\r\n','\r',char(13)),'\n',char(10)),NULL,'tinman61@sasktel.net','3069604159',1,'2025-07-26 18:24:06','2025-07-26T20:16:56.859Z',NULL);
INSERT INTO "tributes" ("id","name","message","image_url","email","phone","approved","created_at","approved_at","admin_notes") VALUES(64,'Colin Smyth',replace(replace('I first met Peter Rhodes in January 1985 when I arrived from the UK to take up an administrative post at the University of Hong Kong.   His was a formidable presence but he turned out to be warm and welcoming.   He immediately invited me to Sunday lunch with his family and was to do much to help me adjust to the peculiar experience of living in Hong Kong.   Not least, he was a witness at my wedding.\r\nPeter had risen rapidly in the faculty of law (of which he was soon to be elected dean) and was involved in many significant projects, including (a sample only) producing  a new faculty handbook, organising the faculty’s  tenth anniversary celebrations (attended by the Lord Chancellor), leading a faculty fundraising campaign, and guiding the introduction of a new degree of  master of International law.\r\nI worked closely with Peter in several faculty and university capacities.   Invariably he lived up to his deserved reputation for honesty, modesty, frankness and commonsense.   Peter did not grandstand or make promises he could not keep.   He spoke only when he had something relevant to say.   What he said counted all as the more for that and was heard with respect.   He was a joy to work with:   well organised, respectful of deadlines, calm, good natured, always careful to acknowledge achievements and successes.   He didn’t shirk from offering an admonition or rebuke when necessary, but did so without malice or offence (I testify to this from first-hand experience).\r\nOn my arrival in 1985 Peter immediately conscripted me to the thrice weekly running group which included frequent attenders such as Michael Jackson, Peter Morrow and Paddy Sheehan with a changing cast of other colleagues and visitors.   For good measure he added three lunchtime gym sessions.   Peter could never be accused of being a sprinter but in his running as in all else he was doggedly persistent and always finished what he had started.   We took part in many races and featured regularly in the annual Matilda Hospital sedan chair charity event.   During my eleven years in Hong Kong, we ran hundreds of hours together, as Connie Carmichael has written, ‘’up and over and around the mountains of Hong Kong Island’.   As we gained seniority in the university, it became more difficult to find time to run together but we managed to keep going quite regularly.   Our last run together was on Saturday 23 March 1996 when a group of five (Peter, Cathay Chan, Bakr Rabie, W K Chan and I) finished the eight-mile Peel Rise run in two hours.   Hardly a record but the end of an era.\r\nAfter leaving Hong Kong University Peter and I kept in touch and met in Auckland and Hong Kong from time to time.   In 2017 he and Conniie invited my wife, Stella, my son, Freddy, and me for dinner at their Taipo home.   They were as always generous hosts, and Peter was obviously as keen as ever about his professional activities and working with students.  Sadly, that was to be our last meeting.\r\nWe send our heartfelt condolences to Connie, Graham and Jean\r\n\r\n','\r',char(13)),'\n',char(10)),NULL,'colin51smyth@gmail.com','+61 419 189 128',1,'2025-07-27 07:38:00','2025-07-27T16:49:07.395Z',NULL);
INSERT INTO "tributes" ("id","name","message","image_url","email","phone","approved","created_at","approved_at","admin_notes") VALUES(65,'Madli Rohtla','I met Peter through my friendship with her daughter Jean back in the late 2000''s. During our high school years in Hong Kong as well as in the subsequent years, Peter and Connie shared their hospitality and kindness with me and other classmates living far away from home. I will always remember the warmth and the welcoming atmosphere of their home, and the ease with which we connected. My deepest condolences go to Peter''s family on his passing. ',NULL,'madli.rohtla@gmail.com','+36 30 313 2045',1,'2025-07-27 13:03:12','2025-07-27T16:49:14.423Z',NULL);
INSERT INTO "tributes" ("id","name","message","image_url","email","phone","approved","created_at","approved_at","admin_notes") VALUES(66,'Moonar tsoi',replace(replace('**A Tribute to Professor Peter Rhodes: Mentor, Scholar, and Guiding Light**\r\n\r\nThe news of Professor Peter Rhodes'' passing has left a profound sense of loss, not just within the halls of CUHK’s Faculty of Law, but deeply within the hearts of those of us fortunate enough to call him teacher, mentor, and friend. As his former student and Vis Moot tutee, I feel a unique weight of gratitude and sorrow, compelled to honour the extraordinary man who shaped so many minds and careers.\r\n\r\nProfessor Rhodes wasn''t merely the Dean; he was the very embodiment of academic excellence, intellectual rigour, and unwavering dedication. His leadership steered us with vision and integrity, but for those of us in smaller classrooms or huddled over moot problems, he was something even more vital: **an exceptional tutor and mentor**.\r\n\r\nMy most vivid memories of Professor Rhodes stem from the intense, exhilarating crucible of the Vis Moot. As our tutor, he didn''t just teach international commercial law; he *immersed* us in it. He approached each session, each practice oral, each draft memorial, with a rare combination of **keen insight, meticulous attention to detail, and genuine investment in our growth**. He possessed an uncanny ability to dissect complex legal arguments while simultaneously building our confidence. He challenged our assumptions, pushed us beyond our perceived limits, and demanded precision – not for its own sake, but because he believed fiercely in the power of well-reasoned law and clear advocacy.\r\n\r\nHe inspired us to dig deeper, research harder, and articulate more clearly. Behind his sharp legal mind was a palpable **kindness and patience**. He listened intently, offered constructive criticism that felt like guidance rather than judgment, and celebrated our breakthroughs, however small. He understood the pressure we were under and became a pillar of calm, experienced support.\r\n\r\nProfessor Rhodes taught us far more than CISG articles or arbitration procedure. He modelled **intellectual curiosity, professional integrity, and the importance of approaching the law with both seriousness and humanity**. He showed us that rigorous scholarship and compassionate mentorship are not mutually exclusive but are, in fact, the hallmarks of a truly great legal educator.\r\n\r\nAs his student, I witnessed firsthand his dedication not just to the institution of CUHK, but to the individuals within it. He remembered his students, followed their journeys, and took genuine pride in their successes. His door, both literally and figuratively, always seemed open – a rare quality in someone of his stature.\r\n\r\nThe legal community has lost a towering scholar and leader. But we, his students, have lost something deeply personal: a mentor who saw potential within us and tirelessly worked to help us realize it. He didn''t just teach us law; he helped shape us into the lawyers and people we are today.\r\n\r\nProfessor Rhodes, thank you for your unwavering belief, your invaluable guidance during those formative Vis Moot days, and for setting an enduring example of excellence, dedication, and quiet wisdom. Your legacy lives on not only in the annals of CUHK but in the careers and character of every student you inspired. You will be profoundly missed, but never forgotten.\r\n\r\nRest in peace, Professor.\r\n','\r',char(13)),'\n',char(10)),'/api/images/tribute-1753671866687-y0b1mnt69.jpeg','tsoimungfan@gmail.com',NULL,1,'2025-07-28 03:04:29','2025-07-28T12:35:21.416Z',NULL);
INSERT INTO "tributes" ("id","name","message","image_url","email","phone","approved","created_at","approved_at","admin_notes") VALUES(67,'Michael Olesnicky','I was shocked when Connie informed me of Peter''s passing. I met Peter over 40 years ago when I was a youngster arriving in Hong Kong to teach at the Law Faculty in HKU, and we immediately bonded as colleagues and friends. Peter never really liked administration (or so he said) and reserved his passion for teaching, and the many tributes that have been posted by his students and colleagues attest to that. His legacy as a teacher is one of rigorous scholarship, academic leadership and a heartfelt commitment to nurturing his students, and his legacy as an individual are the family members who have survived him. Farewell my friend.',NULL,'michael@olesnicky.com','+85298378049',1,'2025-07-28 08:58:46','2025-07-28T12:35:23.732Z',NULL);
INSERT INTO "tributes" ("id","name","message","image_url","email","phone","approved","created_at","approved_at","admin_notes") VALUES(68,'Newton Mak','Peter is my coach in CUHK Vis and a mentor beyond.  I am blessed to have his encouragement when I most needed it during a career switch.  The father of the Vis family cares deeply about his students and spends precious personal time to foster lasting relationship and mutual support.  I am shocked and saddened by his sudden passing.  I regret not having made more efforts in recent years to keep in touch.  Peter’s life continues to inspire me as I read tributes and memories from others.  Thank you for everything, Peter.  I am forever grateful for your guidance and care.  Rest in peace.  ',NULL,'newsaur@gmail.com',NULL,1,'2025-07-28 09:36:12','2025-07-28T12:35:25.427Z',NULL);
INSERT INTO "tributes" ("id","name","message","image_url","email","phone","approved","created_at","approved_at","admin_notes") VALUES(71,'Wendlandt Hasselle',replace(replace('So sorry for y''all''s loss, Connie, Graham, Jean, and the grandkids.\r\nI was blessed to have gotten to know Peter and Connie on an early tour of China in 1980, when travelling with 2 friends made from on a London-Kathmandu camping trip in ''76 (one of whom was a colleague of Peter''s at HKU).\r\nWhen we suddenly lost our place to stay in HK while awaiting a ship for Singapore, Peter and Connie were kind enough to take us in until our departure!  Over the decades, I''ve enjoyed their delightful annual newsletters, visited them at Harvard, at their last home on campus, hosted Graham here in Mississippi and took him to the Florida coast where he caught his first big fish!, and Peter and Connie came to visit us once for a long weekend while living in San Francisco.  He loved going to see Rhodes College in Memphis and get T-shirts with his last name on them. The last time we saw Peter was at Jean''s law school graduation in Atlanta, when we also watched the Kentucky Derby at my cousin''s house. Peter helped me plan a trip to New Zealand and a recent trip to the Philippines.  Needless to say, we all loved to travel.  I think of Peter as an avid explorer, enthusiastic and kind, a fun, interesting, and delightful conversationalist, but I never saw his professional side that has been so often mentioned!   \r\nCertainly Peter fit in as much far-flung travel as he could during his breaks from teaching.  It seems so apt that he was abroad on vacation when he died, but just VERY sad that he didn''t get to enjoy more of his retirement.\r\nWill miss corresponding with him, and sending love and condolences from Bard and me to your family','\r',char(13)),'\n',char(10)),NULL,NULL,NULL,1,'2025-07-28 17:10:30','2025-07-28T17:11:32.282Z',NULL);
INSERT INTO "tributes" ("id","name","message","image_url","email","phone","approved","created_at","approved_at","admin_notes") VALUES(72,'Jackie Yeung','Thank you Professor - you are the one who taught me that the reasonable man standard is the ordinary man on the Shau Kei Wan tram - I remembered that until now. Tort is also and remains my favourite subject in class - as I struggled to go through my first year as a science student back then from secondary school, and not knowing how to study law school. You also gave me the opportunity to excel further into mooting, which I knew nothing of and was in fact afraid (I didn''t tell you that! since year 2)! I went for being a member, to an oralist for Vis moot, and to a sharing speaker for CUHK and a coach even for the University College London team when I had my masters there. I also met you and your family earlier, and again you in Vienna - but little do I know that that would be the last time...God bless you and your family, life is short, but you reminded me of what the great things we can do, no matter big or small, that would leave a remarkable impact on others'' lives. Thank you once again, Professor. See you later in heaven.',NULL,'dgjacq@gmail.com','+85262131628',1,'2025-07-29 10:59:03','2025-07-29T11:29:38.306Z',NULL);
INSERT INTO "tributes" ("id","name","message","image_url","email","phone","approved","created_at","approved_at","admin_notes") VALUES(73,'DAVE MacKillop',replace(replace('Good day:\r\nEach of you who read this note had a relationship with Peter.  As a colleague, professor, fellow traveller, Kiwi, neighbour…\r\n\r\nTonny and I knew Peter as a friend.\r\n\r\nThis is the story about an adventure that we shared with Connie and Peter.  And a few others.\r\n\r\nConnie Carmichael, Karen Grant, Leslie Barnwell and I met in grade 11/12.  We partied together occasionally, and were in the same graduating class, 1967, Mount Baker Senior Secondary, Cranbrook, British Columbia, Canada.  From there, we went our separate ways, separate lives.\r\n\r\nIn 2018, we met up with each other at our class reunion in Cranbrook.  And our modestly nervous partners  were there as well.  Tonny and I, Karen and Roger, and Connie and Peter.  Leslie’s partner, Rusty, wasn’t able to attend.  Interestingly enough, we all connected.  Tonny mentioned to me that Peter went out of his way to ensure that everyone was included, engaged and comfortable with each other.  \r\n\r\nIn 2023, another class reunion.  All of us had a wonderful time.  At the end of the reunion, the organizer stood up and said, ‘see you in five years”. We looked at each other… Hmmm…..Leslie mentioned the famous Kispiox Music Festival, north of Hazelton.  We decided to attend.  And it was suggested that we should also go to Haida Gwaii, even better.  We spent much of the spring of 2024 organizing that trip.  Ken Carmichael, Connie’s brother was able to join us.  We decided to meet at Leslie’s in Hazelton, and go from there.   (Many of you likely  have only a modest understanding of Canadian Geography, which is understandable. Calgary, where Tonny and I live is 1245 km from Hazelton. Kispiox in north of Hazelton. Hazelton is 270 km from Prince Rupert.  From Prince Rupert you take a 10 hour ferry ride to Haida Gwaii.    From Hong Kong, the flight to Vancouver varies from  14.5 to 17 hours.  Vancouver to Hazelton is about 1,230 km.  From Cranbrook, where Karen lives, to Hazelton, is 1,320 km).  \r\n\r\nTogether we shared a wonderful time.  Magnificent scenery and fine hikes.  Much learning, especially about Indigenous history.  Meals together, travelling together.  Laughing.  Taking photos of the landscape and funny pictures of each other.  And we got to know each other very well.  And although we have led separate lives, to learn how similar we are, and how much we like each other.  \r\nPeter became a wonderful friend to each of us.  He was a bit quiet, but had a humorous side.\r\n\r\nPeter was a good man;  for me, “a good man” is the greatest compliment that any man can earn.  \r\nWe will miss Peter.  \r\n\r\nWith our love,\r\n\r\nDave and Tonny MacKillop:  Calgary, Canada\r\n\r\n','\r',char(13)),'\n',char(10)),NULL,'mackillopdave@yahoo.com','4035195718',1,'2025-07-29 21:51:34','2025-07-30T03:42:39.496Z',NULL);
INSERT INTO "tributes" ("id","name","message","image_url","email","phone","approved","created_at","approved_at","admin_notes") VALUES(74,'Vivian & Neil Cameron',replace(replace('We had three days wonderful days together with Peter and Connie in Doha before setting off on our Safari in Tanzania on the 11th July. Who would have thought that two days later Peter would no longer be with us. Peter had spent twelve months planning this trip for the four of us. Every detail had been meticulously prepared. His wonderful ability to retain so much knowledge about a vast array of topics meant that we were counting on Peter to be our leading guide. How quickly life can change.\r\n\r\nOur friendship with Peter and Connie goes back a long way.  Neil and Peter were at Law School together in Auckland. By coincidence they both obtained lecturing positions at the University of Saskatchewan in 1972. Connie soon came on the scene and from that time on we have been fortunate to have Peter and Connie among our closest of friends. Whist we returned to New Zealand in 1976 we have seen Peter and Connie regularly either through our travels or their numerous visits to NZ.\r\n\r\nGraham and Jean you have been a wonderful tower of support and strength for your mother during this difficult time. For both of you to fly around the world to meet with us all in Tanzania was incredible. We were lucky to spend time with you there before you all departed for HK.\r\n\r\nPeter we will so miss you. We have many wonderful memories and experiences to remember you by.  Tanzania will be a stand out as you were that one that initiated this incredible experience. Rest in peace our dear friend.\r\n\r\nNeil & Vivian Cameron\r\n','\r',char(13)),'\n',char(10)),'/api/images/tribute-1753902896450-ql7ch2u0c.jpeg',NULL,NULL,1,'2025-07-30 19:14:59','2025-07-30T20:17:12.894Z',NULL);
INSERT INTO "tributes" ("id","name","message","image_url","email","phone","approved","created_at","approved_at","admin_notes") VALUES(75,'Lindsay Neilson',replace(replace('I met Peter (and Connie) when I set out into the world at the ripe old age of 24 in 1990 and landed in Hong Kong thinking - what have I done!  Little did I truly realize I was so lucky to spend my first week with them and their little (then) kids.  Jean was just an infant!  They helped explain so much to me about travelling and living in Asia. In fact, I ended up loving it so much, I lived for 10 years in Bangkok. Peter was an important part of my introduction to Hong Kong and Asia. Sending all my love and thoughts to Connie and the entire family \r\n','\r',char(13)),'\n',char(10)),NULL,'lindsay.neilson@shaw.ca',NULL,1,'2025-08-01 17:14:32','2025-08-01T17:19:35.813Z',NULL);
INSERT INTO "tributes" ("id","name","message","image_url","email","phone","approved","created_at","approved_at","admin_notes") VALUES(76,'Michael Lyon',replace(replace('I was shocked and saddened to learn of Peter’s passing. We had just agreed in early June that we would keep in better touch and hoped to meet up, since our last visit was too long ago. We were to meet during my last visit to HK several years ago, but the day of our visit a typhon hit and our plans were sidetracked. I always thought that we would just find another time – I never dreamed that this missed visit would be my last chance for another great meal and conversation with Peter.\r\n\r\nWe met in 1982, when I was doing my JD at Harvard, and volunteered to host international LLM students. I had spent three months backpacking around Asia the summer before law school, including nearly a month in China, and so appreciated the opportunity to discuss Asia with Peter, and his classmate Jeffery Chan (see his post).  I learned so much from these discussions -- Peter made that year a richer experience. As Jeffrey mentioned, a highlight was our drive in my old Toyota to Newport to visit the mansions, see the America’s Cup boats at dock, and have a seafood lunch. One of a few great experiences that year.\r\n\r\nI always found that Peter was driven by tremendous curiosity, which I think helped inspire his passion for the law, but also for global exploration. Last year I travelled to Tanzania with my son prior to his starting university, and we climbed Kilimanjaro and also visited the beautiful safari parks. I am confident that Peter was very much enjoying that amazing experience in Tanzania, with his loving wife Connie and his children on his mind, as his last memories.\r\n\r\nMike Lyon\r\nWashington, DC\r\n','\r',char(13)),'\n',char(10)),NULL,'web@michaellyon.com',NULL,1,'2025-08-02 19:56:39','2025-08-02T21:17:51.076Z',NULL);
INSERT INTO "tributes" ("id","name","message","image_url","email","phone","approved","created_at","approved_at","admin_notes") VALUES(77,'Michael D Pendleton',replace(replace('I met Peter (and Connie) in 1981 when I joined the teaching staff at HKU Law. Peter had a habit of taking people under his wing, as he did me. Kindliness was his number one attribute, generously given to all. \r\n\r\nWith Robyn Martin his Damages for injuries text became a staple for all law offices in HK.\r\n\r\nWhen he became Dean of HKU Law Faculty, students and staff were the beneficiaries. Always fair, generous and kind.\r\n\r\nHis fame as a Jessup and VIS moot coach is know to literally decades of students.  It was above and beyond.\r\n\r\nI met him for lunch and managed to tout him to CUHK, although on terms which should have been much better. \r\n\r\nWhen I stopped occasionally teaching at HKU in 2020 I managed to ingratiate myself into receiving the family Christmas newsletter.  Marvellous to see the travel, the joy, the best of life.\r\n\r\nI''m so very glad I knew Peter. It was a privilege. ','\r',char(13)),'\n',char(10)),NULL,'leahcim53@gmail.com','+64220594217',1,'2025-08-04 00:26:45','2025-08-04T14:02:39.518Z',NULL);
INSERT INTO "tributes" ("id","name","message","image_url","email","phone","approved","created_at","approved_at","admin_notes") VALUES(78,'Doris, Lew, and Andrea Truscott',replace(replace('Our family in New Zealand have been lucky to know Peter from his very early years.\r\n\r\nWe enjoyed many wonderful meals together when Peter, Connie and the family lived in Auckland. They were wonderful evenings with excellent conversations, lots of great memories with Peter and Connie being warm and welcoming hosts.\r\n\r\nPeter really was a gentleman, warm hearted with a wonderful sense of humour you could always share a great conversation with. He was justifiably proud of his wonderful family, and he also loved to sing the praises of the students in Hong Kong of whom he was also proud.\r\n\r\nPeter was taken far too early, there were still many wonderful moments, conversations, and laughs to be shared. Our condolences go to Connie, Graham, Jean and the grandchildren, as well as his brother Mike and all Peters family and friends. Rest in Peace.','\r',char(13)),'\n',char(10)),NULL,'lewtruscott@gmail.com','09274303921',1,'2025-08-04 09:28:05','2025-08-04T14:02:40.753Z',NULL);
INSERT INTO "tributes" ("id","name","message","image_url","email","phone","approved","created_at","approved_at","admin_notes") VALUES(79,'Malcolm Merry',replace(replace('Peter was the first person I met in Hong Kong.  One steamy day in July 1981 he greeted me, a young recruit to a lectureship at HKU''s law school, at the arrivals hall of Kai Tak airport.  He had arranged for the vice-chancellor''s limousine and driver to take us to Pokfulam.  En route he gave a briefing about Hong Kong and told me my new home was a palace: he wasn''t far wrong, it was much too big for a bachelor.  I was impressed.  Even more so when I opened the fridge and found he had stocked it with essentials.\r\nThat was the start of  44-year friendship which has now been abruptly and shockingly severed.   I cannot add to the many appreciations of Peter''s character. talents and career that appear above.  They all ring true and show what a fine friend and colleague he was.','\r',char(13)),'\n',char(10)),NULL,'malcolmjmerry@gmail.com','+447484745584',1,'2025-08-04 10:16:45','2025-08-04T14:02:43.190Z',NULL);
INSERT INTO "tributes" ("id","name","message","image_url","email","phone","approved","created_at","approved_at","admin_notes") VALUES(80,'Anthony QIAO',replace(replace('Peter gave me the most unique law school experience.\r\n\r\nI am easily a very different vis family member compared to all others given my background. But throughout my two years'' experience in the team with Peter, I felt no difference. The team is inclusive, open-minded, and dynamic, thanks to Peter''s philosophy running it. There is no doubt Peter and Vis changed many lives. For me, it is a journey of re-discovering myself when pursuing a new career - a rare second chance in life. I thank Peter for making all this possible.\r\n\r\nSometimes it''s hard to believe Vis had taken up 2/3 of my law school life. All the memory working with Peter on every Wednesday night and the hospitality of Peter and Connie hosting us for all the BBQs still feels fresh and it will be so forever. The legacy of Peter and Vis would carry on in the years to come and continue to influence people - and I will always be passing the spirits of the team to the person next to me. \r\n\r\nThanks Peter for being a fantastic coach, an inspiring mentor, and a cheerful friend. Thanks Connie for always taking care of us and supporting us in Hong Kong and Vienna. Thanks all others for giving their best to the team throughout the years. Nothing can compare to the moments we had together as a team and as a family. \r\n','\r',char(13)),'\n',char(10)),'/api/images/tribute-1754459427120-sbm7z7ze9.jpeg','anthony.qiao.yuanwu@gmail.com','85291413540',1,'2025-08-06 05:50:29','2025-08-06T14:24:39.906Z',NULL);
INSERT INTO "tributes" ("id","name","message","image_url","email","phone","approved","created_at","approved_at","admin_notes") VALUES(81,'Terri Mottershead','An exceptional colleague, friend, and teacher dedicated to his family, friends, teaching, and students. I looked forward to my chats with Peter, and benefited enormously from his generosity, friendship and counsel. My heartfelt condolences to Connie, Graham, Jean and his whole family. He will be greatly missed.',NULL,'tm@mottersheadconsulting.com','+61448220190',1,'2025-08-10 07:40:19','2025-08-10T11:39:39.462Z',NULL);
INSERT INTO "tributes" ("id","name","message","image_url","email","phone","approved","created_at","approved_at","admin_notes") VALUES(82,'Peter Wesley-Smith','Peter was so fit, so well-organised and efficient that it doesn''t seem right that he''s gone. He was a great friend of the faculty at HKU and no doubt at CUHK as well, and he provided reliable leadership through some difficult times. I remember well his desk at the end of the working day: not a scrap of paper or anything else on it. I could never understand how he did it. Other Deans at HKU Law were bewildered by such an achievement. And by his thorough-going cheerfulness. He was well-liked and admired. We were well-served by his personal qualities and his determination to do well as a leader. I shall always remember him with fondness, gratitude and respect.',NULL,'peterws@shoalhaven.net.au','peterws@shoalhaven.net.au',1,'2025-08-10 21:36:35','2025-08-10T22:54:34.183Z',NULL);
INSERT INTO "tributes" ("id","name","message","image_url","email","phone","approved","created_at","approved_at","admin_notes") VALUES(83,'Duncan Macfarlane',replace(replace('I feel greatly honoured to have known such a kind and good-hearted gentleman in every sense of the word.  Without a shadow of doubt he ranks at the very pinnacle of but a few good friends as he was absolutely exemplary in so so many ways, always smiling, always happy to help others, and to share his wonderful joy of life.\r\n\r\nI was very fortunate to meet Peter in the HKU SCR shortly after I arrived at HKU in 1994 to join the Sport Centre and he was integral in helping me adjust to HKU life and able to cajole me into joining the HKU Staff Hockey team that remained a hallmark and source of several tremendous friendships of my time in Hong Kong - plus numerous discussions on how our beloved All Blacks were progressing, as well as several participations in the HKU Veteran''s team in the Matilda Sedan Chair Race (photo attached).  It was only in early June this year he sent a digital copy of a lovely photo of some of our great hockey colleagues taken at Kings Park that Peter discovered whilst clearing up some of his files and we had a nice email exchange of Peter and Connie''s likely plans for retirement.\r\n\r\nThe world has lost a truly truly giant personality and gracious leader, academic, teacher, and genuinely wonderful man, husband and father.    The world is a much smaller place without him - he touched the hearts of so many people and will be greatly missed by them all.','\r',char(13)),'\n',char(10)),'/api/images/tribute-1754880905643-6539b98i6.jpeg','ldmachk@gmail.com','+61432781201',1,'2025-08-11 02:55:07','2025-08-11T04:38:15.907Z',NULL);
INSERT INTO "tributes" ("id","name","message","image_url","email","phone","approved","created_at","approved_at","admin_notes") VALUES(84,'Ian Sun Liu',replace(replace('Thank you, for everything, Peter.\r\n \r\nTo me, Peter was a Professor, Coach, Counsellor, and—foremost—a friend. When I joined CUHK Law as a first-year student, I had no idea that one of the first professors I would meet—quiet, grandfatherly, and incredibly kind—would become such a lasting part of my journey. I still remember his Vis Team introduction: “Standing on the shoulders of giants.” At the time, I didn’t realize I was already doing exactly that.\r\n \r\nProfessor Rhodes was my academic counsellor from day one. He took a genuine interest in my background, which made me feel seen and welcomed in the classroom. I still remember his Torts lectures: deliberate in delivery and deeply thoughtful. The pace wasn’t just style—it was care. He taught with clarity so that even those of us who weren’t native English speakers could follow, understand, and grow. And I miss our conversations before class—those conversations that somehow made the day feel steadier.\r\n \r\nLater on, as I began navigating the daunting world of job applications, it was Professor Rhodes who still saw my potential. He supported me without hesitation, offering guidance and reminding me of my worth in moments when I doubted it.\r\n \r\nAnd of course, it was again Professor Rhodes who encouraged me to join the Vis Team when I said I wanted to improve my legal writing. That decision became one of the most formative experiences of my legal education. He taught me how to write, how to think, and most of all, how to carry myself. \r\n \r\nLittle did I know, from that very first month of law school, I was being guided by someone whose influence would stay with me for years to come—and for the years that are to come. In his quiet way, he taught, he coached, he believed—and in doing so, he lifted me.\r\n \r\nNow, I find myself wondering how I will be guided.\r\nBut then I remember: his voice, his values, and his example.\r\nHe offered guidance with patience and care—lessons I will continue to draw upon in the years ahead.\r\n \r\nProfessor Peter Rhodes was a monumental mentor.\r\nAnd now, looking back, I understand:\r\nAll along, I was standing on the shoulders of a giant.','\r',char(13)),'\n',char(10)),'/api/images/tribute-1754890795917-f0xqfh4tm.jpeg','liusunian@yahoo.in','+85262919424',1,'2025-08-11 05:39:57','2025-08-11T13:12:49.843Z',NULL);
INSERT INTO "tributes" ("id","name","message","image_url","email","phone","approved","created_at","approved_at","admin_notes") VALUES(85,'Katie Coupar-Evans','I only had the pleasure of knowing Peter for a couple of years and in reconnecting with this part of my family through an extraordinary set of coincidences and luck! I am very sorry to hear of Peter’s passing. His generous spirit and kindness are qualities that I experienced and are echoed in the many beautiful tributes here. I am very saddened by this news and send my deepest condolences to his family, friends and colleagues. It is wonderful to see the way in which he touched so many lives and I am very glad that I was able to have the privilege of knowing him, albeit briefly.',NULL,NULL,NULL,1,'2025-08-11 08:11:06','2025-08-11T13:12:56.050Z',NULL);
INSERT INTO "tributes" ("id","name","message","image_url","email","phone","approved","created_at","approved_at","admin_notes") VALUES(86,'Peter MacKinnon','In addition to my personal tribute conveyed earlier, I would like to add a word about Peter’s time at the College of Law, University of Saskatchewan, Canada. Most importantly, it was there that he met Connie and began the family life that later added Jean and Graham. He was also one of the best and most appreciated of the professors there. So many times I heard one student say to others: “0h you have Peter Rhodes as one of your professors; how lucky you are.” And Peter’s participation in College and University life was excellent and appreciated long after he and Connie moved to Hong Kong. I am a former dean of the College and, to this day, I continue to encounter Peter’s former students and colleagues who recall his days at University of Saskatchewan with admiration and affection.',NULL,'rpetermackinnon@gmail.com','(403) 493-1232',1,'2025-08-12 13:02:00','2025-08-12T15:21:19.590Z',NULL);
INSERT INTO "tributes" ("id","name","message","image_url","email","phone","approved","created_at","approved_at","admin_notes") VALUES(87,' Roy Delbyck',replace(replace('Hearing about Peter''s passing was  a shot in the gut.  The world is just a lesser place without  him in it.  I first met Peter in the late ''80s or early ''90s when I was practicing at the HK office of Baker & McKenzie.  I think it was Michael Olesnicky or maybe Andrew Halkyard who  put me in Peter''s path by suggesting that I might want  to be a guest lecturer  at the international business/trade graduate class that Peter was then teaching at HKU Law School.  I did that for a few years and then Peter and  I lost touch , reconnecting some time later through  Royal Asiatic Society Hong Kong events and a shared interest in  Shanghai''s   history.   My wife Tracy and I had the pleasure of  being invited by Peter and Connie for a few meals  at their place up at Chinese U where we meet Graham and Lizzie and Austen.  Like all of you,  the memories of Peter course through the brain.  One thing stands out,  that being  the bemused and twinkle-in-eye  quality  with which Peter would pose a question usually (and especially recently) about some  inexplicable and unjustifiable direction my country (the US) was heading in, along the lines of "Roy, now what do you think about ..."  Not an attack at all  but just a gentle nudge to enlighten him  about the unelightenable!  \r\n\r\n I will miss him very  much.  ','\r',char(13)),'\n',char(10)),NULL,'roydelbyck@delbycklawoffices.com','852-2810-5888',1,'2025-08-14 00:08:36','2025-08-14T05:21:15.027Z',NULL);
INSERT INTO "tributes" ("id","name","message","image_url","email","phone","approved","created_at","approved_at","admin_notes") VALUES(88,'Annie Tang','I will always remember my first day at Dentons when you asked me to prepare an internal CPD presentation. I am grateful for that invitation as I managed to pull together a presentation and successfully deliver it!  Thank you for your vote of confidence!  Your cheerful personality and contribution to the legal profession in Hong Kong will be forever remembered.  RIP Peter.',NULL,'annie.tang@staranise.com.hk',NULL,1,'2025-08-14 07:19:52','2025-08-17T12:31:57.705Z',NULL);
INSERT INTO "tributes" ("id","name","message","image_url","email","phone","approved","created_at","approved_at","admin_notes") VALUES(89,'Ann Liu','Peter, our beloved coach for the CUHK Vis Moot team, was far more than an educator—he was a fatherly figure whose warmth and wisdom touched us deeply. His passion for the Vis Moot opened our eyes to a once-in-a-lifetime experience, imparting lessons that will guide us forever. He cared deeply for his students and, for example, supported my dream of pursuing postgraduate studies in the UK. I kept in touch with him during my studies, and he always responded with encouraging messages. He once connected me with a younger alumnus who intended to undertake similar studies, allowing us to share our thoughts. Peter always held his students close to his heart, and I am truly blessed to have been one of them. Thank you, Peter, for everything. You will be dearly missed. Rest in peace.','/api/images/tribute-1755161916271-11xdy73wn.jpeg',NULL,NULL,1,'2025-08-14 08:58:39','2025-08-17T12:31:58.970Z',NULL);
INSERT INTO "tributes" ("id","name","message","image_url","email","phone","approved","created_at","approved_at","admin_notes") VALUES(90,'Anthony and Kakai Marr','Peter was a good friend for well over forty years. Kakai and I will miss him. Peter was a gentleman of the old school, always kind and polite and a man you could rely on in a crisis. However a polymath who would quietly beat you at trivial pursuit and then say that the game contained over six thousand questions and protest that he could not possibly know them all! However you would leave thinking that he only knew nearly all of them.  He was always interesting to talk to and you usually left knowing more than you did before. ',NULL,NULL,NULL,1,'2025-08-17 08:32:59','2025-08-17T12:32:04.356Z',NULL);
INSERT INTO "tributes" ("id","name","message","image_url","email","phone","approved","created_at","approved_at","admin_notes") VALUES(91,'nancy csrmichael','see attached image for our message','/api/images/tribute-1755454969125-rkfrhu2o4.jpeg','ncarmichael@sasktel.net','3063749476',0,'2025-08-17 18:22:50',NULL,'-');
INSERT INTO "tributes" ("id","name","message","image_url","email","phone","approved","created_at","approved_at","admin_notes") VALUES(92,'Farzad Salamifar',replace(replace('And the traveler who never fell from grace with the voyage… \r\nAlthough we only twice, one afternoon and evening spanning the Brooklyn Museum, Hoboken, and Jersey City—it was enough to glimpse a man of extraordinary erudition and sense of wonder. \r\nThe banks of the Hudson River on the New Jersey side—which had been part of my unremarkable daily commute, suddenly took on a mythical depth and significance thanks to the rich and “dynamic” conversations on the history of the Katyn massacre, and your singular insights into the history of the World Wars as we sped along the Old Burma Road discussing the birth of the United States and its legal promises. The only thing that could bring us back down from the lofty heights of history, was the unreserved delight that you took at some succulent donuts from Dunk’n Donuts and a good English pub dinner of liver and onions. To contain multitudes is to be all the more profoundly human. \r\nAnd then there was the Iran travel project together that was never realized.\r\nThank you for inculcating your passion in your immediate, and extended family i.e. your many generations of students. Thank you for daring to forge multiple paths within the world of academia and giving the vocation of teacher its true and fullest meaning. Among the books and presents you gifted me, the Yukio Mishima book will have a special place in my library.\r\n','\r',char(13)),'\n',char(10)),'/api/images/tribute-1755571652153-oekksmvoi.png',NULL,NULL,0,'2025-08-19 02:47:33',NULL,'-');
INSERT INTO "tributes" ("id","name","message","image_url","email","phone","approved","created_at","approved_at","admin_notes") VALUES(93,'Farzad Salamifar',replace(replace('And the traveler who never fell from grace with the voyage…\r\n\r\nAlthough we only met twice, one afternoon and evening spanning the Brooklyn Museum, Hoboken, and Jersey City—it was enough to glimpse a man of extraordinary erudition and sense of wonder.\r\n\r\nThe banks of the Hudson River on the New Jersey side—which had been part of my unremarkable daily commute, suddenly took on a mythical depth and significance thanks to the rich and “dynamic” conversations on the history of the Katyn massacre, and your singular insights into the history of the World Wars as we sped along the Old Burma Road discussing the birth of the United States and its legal promises. The only thing that could bring us back down from the lofty heights of history was the unreserved delight that you took at some succulent donuts from Dunk’n Donuts followed by a good English pub dinner of liver and onions. To contain multitudes is to be all the more profoundly human.\r\n\r\nAnd then there was the Iran travel project together that was never realized.\r\n\r\nThank you for inculcating your passion in your immediate, and extended family i.e. your many generations of students. Thank you for daring to forge multiple paths within the world of academia and giving the vocation of teacher its true and fullest meaning.\r\n\r\nAmong the books and presents you gifted me, the Yukio Mishima book will have a special place in my library. ','\r',char(13)),'\n',char(10)),'/api/images/tribute-1755574861414-mkhhpvra9.png',NULL,NULL,1,'2025-08-19 03:41:03','2025-08-19T03:47:37.188Z',NULL);
INSERT INTO "tributes" ("id","name","message","image_url","email","phone","approved","created_at","approved_at","admin_notes") VALUES(94,'Emma Myers (nee Mellow)','This is such incredibly sad news, and I send my deep condolences to Peter''s family and friends.  Peter was a kind and generous man, who loved his family and was so highly respected. Our families became friends in the 1990s, when Jean and I went to school together. Years later he was good enough, with Connie, to host me when I was in Hong Kong in 2010. I remember being picked up at the airport by them, shown around and taken out for delicious dinners - they made me feel so welcome at their house and it made me as a nervous first-time solo traveller so comfortable. I will always remember this kindness. Sending so many thoughts and strength to his family at this time of loss. ',NULL,'em.mellow@gmail.com',NULL,1,'2025-08-19 04:36:06','2025-08-19T19:27:13.548Z',NULL);
INSERT INTO "tributes" ("id","name","message","image_url","email","phone","approved","created_at","approved_at","admin_notes") VALUES(95,'Nancy Carmichael','see attached file. ','/api/images/tribute-1755906809060-kijm6nm5l.jpeg','ncarmichael@sasktel.net','3063749476',1,'2025-08-22 23:53:29','2025-08-23T14:34:54.325Z',NULL);
INSERT INTO "tributes" ("id","name","message","image_url","email","phone","approved","created_at","approved_at","admin_notes") VALUES(96,'Jasmine Chan','Peter is a well-respected professor. He is always humble. Even at his retirement dinner, he prepared slides, recording the achievement of his VIS team and beloved students. Instead of focusing on how he led the team, he focused on what his students achieved and that is what makes him proud. The way how he devoted all his life in educating future generation is also inspiring.  He constantly reminded his VIS team that “attitude is more important than ability”. This reminder laid a solid cornerstone for me to start my first career - training in a US firm. My willing-to-learn attitude was recognised by my former boss and I managed to survive a tough environment for around 6 years. I am now embarking on a new journey at offshore firm but his teaching will forever remain in my heart. ',NULL,'chanjasmine.aiesec@gmail.com','+85261800306',1,'2025-08-23 15:46:45','2025-08-24T06:48:35.465Z',NULL);
INSERT INTO "tributes" ("id","name","message","image_url","email","phone","approved","created_at","approved_at","admin_notes") VALUES(97,'Kweiman  Tang',replace(replace('A Tribute to Peter Rhodes\r\n\r\nPeter was a part of our walking group for many years. Though his workload kept him busy, he and Connie joined us whenever they could. It was always fun thanks to his gregarious personality, and he was so determined to complete every trail.\r\n\r\nWe would work up a great sweat and then go for a good meal afterwards. Our days together always ended in great joy.\r\n\r\nPeter was looking forward to joining us more regularly after his retirement. It''s a pity that this will not be possible, but he will be with us in spirit.\r\n\r\nWe''ll miss you, Peter.\r\nKweiman\r\n\r\n','\r',char(13)),'\n',char(10)),'/api/images/tribute-1756064366101-z5s8nyxxe.jpeg','kweiman.cdj@gmail.com','85298105141',0,'2025-08-24 19:39:28',NULL,NULL);
INSERT INTO "tributes" ("id","name","message","image_url","email","phone","approved","created_at","approved_at","admin_notes") VALUES(98,'Kweiman  Tang',replace(replace('A Tribute to Peter Rhodes\r\n\r\nPeter was a part of our walking group for many years. Though his workload kept him busy, he and Connie joined us whenever they could. It was always fun thanks to his gregarious personality, and he was so determined to complete every trail.\r\n\r\nWe would work up a great sweat and then go for a good meal afterwards. Our days together always ended in great joy.\r\n\r\nPeter was looking forward to joining us more regularly after his retirement. It''s a pity that this will not be possible, but he will be with us in spirit.\r\n\r\nWe''ll miss you, Peter.\r\nKweiman','\r',char(13)),'\n',char(10)),'/api/images/tribute-1756064591675-po9zd6pz8.jpeg','kweiman.cdj@gmail.com','85298105141',1,'2025-08-24 19:43:13','2025-08-24T23:55:14.965Z',NULL);
INSERT INTO "tributes" ("id","name","message","image_url","email","phone","approved","created_at","approved_at","admin_notes") VALUES(99,'Anonymous','It feels as if it was only yesterday that I was in Professor Rhodes’ lecture hall taking his Tort law class. As a first year student who struggled to adapt to law school life, attending Professor Rhodes’ classes was one of the very few things I looked forward to at school. He was a humorous, encouraging and dedicated teacher. Thank you for everything. We all miss you very much.',NULL,NULL,NULL,1,'2025-08-25 18:58:14','2025-08-27T06:11:10.463Z',NULL);
INSERT INTO "tributes" ("id","name","message","image_url","email","phone","approved","created_at","approved_at","admin_notes") VALUES(100,'Leanne Tse',replace(replace('Peter was the most inspiring, caring and supportive mentor. I am very fortunate to have him as my mentor during my LLB at the CUHK law faculty, but his influence on me actually started before I entered CUHK. When I was chosing what to study for my undergraduate and was deeply troubled by my indecision over whether or not to do law, a family friend who knew Peter suggested me to have a chat with him. It was supposed to be nerve-racking, telling a future law professor you''re not sure about doing law, but Peter patiently gave me very objective advice, shared his experience and insights on how a legal background can be highly versatile.\r\n\r\nIt was lovely meeting up with him and Connie 3 years ago at M+, to show him the place I work at now and how his advice back in 2007 had led me to my current dream job: just like how he told me - I can utlilise my legal knowledge in the art museum world. Without his encouragement back then and unfailing support during the different stages of my university life, I would not be where I am today. I will be forever grateful for all his advice and support. \r\n\r\nWe will all miss you, Peter, but your influence on us will live on forever.','\r',char(13)),'\n',char(10)),'/api/images/tribute-1756305664072-bcejhexfg.jpeg',NULL,NULL,1,'2025-08-27 14:41:06','2025-08-28T01:45:57.232Z',NULL);
INSERT INTO "tributes" ("id","name","message","image_url","email","phone","approved","created_at","approved_at","admin_notes") VALUES(101,'Julienne Jen',replace(replace('I only got to know Peter personally during his last few years at CUHK when I was working with Connie for some PCLL teaching at HKU.  I was lucky enough to be able to meet Peter at their residence on a couple of occasions and each time, Peter would welcome me with his warm smile and he would always share his stories with me and chat with me about my work at HKU.  I am extremely saddened by Peter''s unexpected departure and can feel the loss of his students and of all those whom he has mentored.  \r\nI will always remember Peter as a most passionate and dedicated educator and thank Peter for all the hard work he had done for the HK legal profession.\r\nI send my most sincere condolences to Connie and the family.\r\nWith best regards,\r\nJulienne Jen\r\n','\r',char(13)),'\n',char(10)),NULL,'jjen@hku.hk',NULL,1,'2025-08-28 02:34:43','2025-08-28T14:40:19.674Z',NULL);
INSERT INTO "tributes" ("id","name","message","image_url","email","phone","approved","created_at","approved_at","admin_notes") VALUES(102,'Kay Francis Lawrie',replace(replace(' "A Mighty Totara Has Fallen".\r\nKia Ora Peter, Connie, Graham, Jean and Mike!\r\nAs I sit on the other side of the world in Auckland I reflect that we are now into the fourth generation of family friendships. I was probably 6 years old when you first appeared for a weekend dinner after starting secondary school at St Pauls College. Everyone knows boarding school food is barely edible and my Mum was a great cook! I don''t actually recall a time in my life without you and Mike. I still remember when Aunty Pat and Uncle Dusty (who I adored) moved to NZ. The parties, the food (yes Aunty Pat could cook as well as Myra), and all those darn DISHES (no dish washers in those days). \r\nYou and Connie hosted Mum for her first and only overseas trip, to Hong Kong/China. Mum was forever grateful for that trip. Only one issue was when the hairdresser accidentally chopped Mums very long hair off! \r\nI wonder if you realise how proud your Mum and Dad were of all your achievements. Especially when you were the youngest person to be presented to the Bar at that time. Your photographic memory...you never looked down on the rest of us mere mortals. Connie came along and made you complete! And then the kids arrived and we all held our breath to see if Peter could cope with the fact that babies don''t run well on ''lists''. However you did cope and now it is Graham worrying how he can keep your excellent behaviours alive for his kids. It meant a lot to me to be Grahams Godmother. \r\nPeter, you have always been a good man. Even as a youth there was something about you that set you apart. A good boy that grew rapidly into a great man. From a very young age you used to take your Mum around all her friends (mostly old ladies) when you were home from Canada or Hong Kong. You never moaned about this.\r\nYour attributes are many: son, brother, husband, father, grandfather, friend, colleague. Humble, huge capacity for study, thirst for travel, ability to converse with anyone, anywhere, any age! Respectful of young and old. An open mind served you well. A man of the world/people. It is easy to see why so many people have your footprints on their minds and hearts. \r\nThanks for the memories.\r\nHe aha te mea nui o te ao?\r\nHe tangata, he tangata, he tangata!\r\n(What is the most important thing in the world?\r\nIt is people, it is people, it is people!)\r\n\r\nRest In Peace Peter!\r\n\r\nBlessings to all the family!\r\n\r\nArohanui.\r\nKay (on behalf of the Lawrie/Cull whanau)','\r',char(13)),'\n',char(10)),NULL,'kayflawrie@gmail.com','+6421552974',1,'2025-08-28 10:36:56','2025-08-28T14:40:25.807Z',NULL);
INSERT INTO "tributes" ("id","name","message","image_url","email","phone","approved","created_at","approved_at","admin_notes") VALUES(103,'Brenda Green','I was the Regional Administrator for Winston & Strawn, which employed Peter as a Consultant.  It was my great honor to work with him.  Peter was first and foremost a wonderful person.  He was happy, pleasant, helpful,  warm and caring.   Everyone who worked with him loved him.   In addition, Peter was a consummate professional---knowledgeable, hardworking, reliable and effective.   As our working relationship developed, I was fortunate to be able to call Peter a friend.  I send my heartfelt condolences to Peter''s family.  He was a lovely man and will be sorely missed.  May Peter rest in peace.',NULL,'brendagreen888@yahoo.com','19418822689',1,'2025-08-28 16:35:07','2025-08-29T00:52:50.129Z',NULL);
INSERT INTO "tributes" ("id","name","message","image_url","email","phone","approved","created_at","approved_at","admin_notes") VALUES(104,'Anil Verma',replace(replace('Remembering Peter\r\n\r\nI knew Peter initially only as Connie’s partner. It was 1974 when I first arrived in Saskatoon (Canada) to join the MBA program in which Connie was also enrolled. Both Connie and Peter soon became friends as we discovered our shared interest in travel and history. I found Peter to be a warm person who had a good feel for different cultures. He not only understood our differences but also respected them.\r\n\r\nAlthough my field is not law Connie kept me updated on his numerous accomplishments in law. Despite his considerable stature in the field he remained humble, approachable and modest. This says a great deal about who he was at the core. \r\n\r\nOver half-a-century, we kept in touch. After Saskatoon we had another overlapping year in Cambridge, MA, when Peter spent a year at the Harvard Law School and I became a PhD student at MIT. We had several memorable excursions from our base in Boston. \r\n\r\nI visited Peter and Connie on several occasions in HK where Peter was ever the enthusiastic trip planner for our brief stays. Whether I was there for a day or a whole week, Peter would make us a daily plan on “must-do-must-see” things. He loved different places and cultures and foods and loved to share with his friends what he found exciting around him. His enthusiasm was infectious.\r\n\r\nThere was at least one topic on which we saw things differently. One example would be the British Empire. Peter was a fan of sorts who liked the idea of the Commonwealth in which a group of former British colonies came together to share ideas and programs. I, as a person born in India, was less enamored of the British Empire. Yet, he more-than-bridged the gap for me by acknowledging the brutality and cruelty of European colonizers in many parts of the Americas, Asia and Africa. I realized that underneath all the Empire hype, Peter was a discerning reader and interpreter of history.\r\n\r\nI was hoping to host Connie and Peter in Lima (Peru) where we are currently living. Peter was interested and we exchanged emails to see how we might proceed. Alas, that never came to fruition. This leaves me wishing that he were still around. I shall miss him terribly.\r\nAnil Verma\r\nLima\r\n28 August 2025','\r',char(13)),'\n',char(10)),NULL,'anilverma59@yahoo.com',NULL,1,'2025-08-28 18:25:11','2025-08-29T00:53:04.843Z',NULL);
INSERT INTO "tributes" ("id","name","message","image_url","email","phone","approved","created_at","approved_at","admin_notes") VALUES(105,'Nels','So sad to hear of the passing of Professor Peter Rhodes. He was always so kind to me and my family. It was incredible to read about his life and accomplishments. Sending all my love to Connie, Graham, and Jean. If I am in Hong Kong, I will definitely attend the memorial service; if not, I will be present on the live stream.',NULL,NULL,NULL,1,'2025-08-28 19:33:48','2025-08-29T00:54:18.857Z',NULL);
INSERT INTO "tributes" ("id","name","message","image_url","email","phone","approved","created_at","approved_at","admin_notes") VALUES(106,'John McKelvie',replace(replace('Hi Connie –\r\n\r\nIt’s John McKelvie here, saying I’m really sorry to hear about Peter passing away. These are difficult emails to write, of course, but it’s worse to not say anything.\r\n\r\nI first met Peter and Mike when I was very young. Our parents were good friends in Hong Kong. I can recall Peter teaching me chess, when I was too young to understand the intricacies of checkmate, just understanding the way the various pieces moved - so he surrendered all his pieces just after slaughtering mine, so we had just kings left on an empty board. I then pursued his around until he declared he was cornered and couldn’t escape, and so ceded the game. I can recall telling my father how good I was, who said something to the effect that Peter was both a good player and also very kind.\r\n\r\nIf you’re ever back in NZ again, let me know. Keep in touch.','\r',char(13)),'\n',char(10)),NULL,NULL,NULL,1,'2025-08-29 06:14:28','2025-08-30T00:32:20.356Z',NULL);
INSERT INTO "tributes" ("id","name","message","image_url","email","phone","approved","created_at","approved_at","admin_notes") VALUES(107,'Helen Tinsley','On ',NULL,'fulttins@netvigator.com','+85290342241',0,'2025-08-29 23:01:47',NULL,NULL);
INSERT INTO "tributes" ("id","name","message","image_url","email","phone","approved","created_at","approved_at","admin_notes") VALUES(108,'Helen Tinsley',' On O ON ',NULL,'fulttins@netvigator.com','+85290342241',0,'2025-08-29 23:07:05',NULL,NULL);
INSERT INTO "tributes" ("id","name","message","image_url","email","phone","approved","created_at","approved_at","admin_notes") VALUES(109,'Ryan Reetz','I got to know Peter through the happiest of coincidences - during her law school studies, his daughter Jean learned of my enthusiasm for the Vis Moot (obviously, a passion of Peter''s) and arranged to introduce us.  During the next year''s moot, my wife Susanne and I met Peter and Connie in person, and spending time with them became one of the highlights of our trips to Vienna.  Peter was remarkable for so many things: his intelligence, charisma, love of teaching and dedication to his students, to name just a few.  He is deeply missed.  But his presence still resonates in the lives of the innumerable people whom he taught, befriended, guided, inspired, and loved.',NULL,'ryan.reetz@bclplaw.com',NULL,1,'2025-08-30 00:26:48','2025-08-30T00:33:11.503Z',NULL);
INSERT INTO "tributes" ("id","name","message","image_url","email","phone","approved","created_at","approved_at","admin_notes") VALUES(110,'The Hong Kong Natural History Society','In the world of natural history, we are often reminded of the interconnectedness of all life. Peter''s contributions and enthusiasm have undoubtedly left a lasting ripple in the lives of the members who were fortunate to meet him, much like the enduring marks of nature itself.','/api/images/tribute-1756513878443-mf1aembyd.png','hknhscommittee@gmail.com','+85267486940',1,'2025-08-30 00:31:20','2025-08-30T00:33:13.616Z',NULL);
INSERT INTO "tributes" ("id","name","message","image_url","email","phone","approved","created_at","approved_at","admin_notes") VALUES(111,'Royal Asiatic Society Hong Kong',replace(replace('On behalf of  Council and members of the Royal Asiatic Society Hong Kong, we send our sincere condolences on Peter’s passing to his family and colleagues . He was a member of RASHK since 2002 and a regular attendee at many of our events, frequently in support of his wife Connie, who is our respected Honorary Treasurer.  His support was always interested and  generous, often asking some important questions on the content of our presentation and visits. His contribution was very much appreciated.  It was clear that he was a much admired and  highly respected member of the legal community, who loved teaching and was very proud of his students, both present and past.  \r\n\r\nHis sudden and untimely passing, shortly after retiring, leaves a significant gap in our membership. He will be sorely missed. May he now rest peacefully.\r\n\r\nInstead of flowers for today’s Memorial, we will send a donation to our related trust, The Ride Fund, which supports local publications of Hong Kong’s history','\r',char(13)),'\n',char(10)),'/api/images/tribute-1756515922557-x3zibwzx2.jpeg',NULL,NULL,1,'2025-08-30 01:05:23','2025-08-30T01:15:48.000Z',NULL);
INSERT INTO "tributes" ("id","name","message","image_url","email","phone","approved","created_at","approved_at","admin_notes") VALUES(112,'陳維田 (Daniel Chan)',replace(replace('The phrase “his presence lingers” （音容宛在） is not just a polite expression for Peter. Since his passing a few months ago, his voice and smile have stayed with me, vivid in my heart.\r\n\r\nI first met Peter on July 5, 2020, the day my daughter Elizabeth married his son, Craham. That day, I saw Peter’s warm, elegant smile and kind face for the first time, and it left a lasting impression.\r\n\r\nPeter loved to travel. At every gathering, he would eagerly share photos from his trips and recount amusing stories. His detailed observations of local customs and cultures revealed his deep curiosity about the world. Through his words, you could feel the joy he found in traveling with his family. He once said that the greatest fulfillment in life was spending happy moments with loved ones, even if they did not live under the same roof.\r\n\r\nBoth of us were university professors—I in engineering, he in law. We sometimes talked about the challenges of guiding students today. Artificial intelligence (AI) has been a double-edged sword: it boosts learning but also fosters over-reliance and, at times, academic dishonesty. Peter, with his profound knowledge, handled teaching, mentoring, and organizing mock trial activities with ease. To me, a fellow academic, his tireless dedication and ability to keep up with the times made him a true role model in higher education.\r\n\r\nOn two occasions, Peter and I sat together at the cozy coffee shop near the train station on the Chinese University campus. We chatted about everything under the sun, and those moments were relaxed and joyful. He shared his plans for future travels, and I thought we would have more chances to meet there. But life had other plans. Now, whenever I walk the sloping path to the University Station platform on my way to the mainland, I cannot help but glance at that coffee shop, where Peter’s gentle smile seems to linger in my mind.\r\n\r\nA Christian friend once described heaven as a place where you can travel endlessly. For Peter, perhaps this is not an end but a new beginning. May he explore new horizons every day, embraced by God’s love and grace.\r\n\r\nLife is fleeting, and those who leave us are gone, but Peter’s memory remains vivid in my heart. This, I believe, is the truest meaning of “his presence lingers.”','\r',char(13)),'\n',char(10)),NULL,NULL,NULL,1,'2025-08-30 01:35:55','2025-08-30T01:53:14.552Z',NULL);
INSERT INTO "tributes" ("id","name","message","image_url","email","phone","approved","created_at","approved_at","admin_notes") VALUES(113,'Janet Pang','Professor Rhodes, thank you so much for being our best first teacher at CUHK LLB. Thank you for your interesting classes. We were lucky to have you so we were not intimidated by law as we first started!',NULL,'hoyanpang@gmail.com','97473433',1,'2025-08-30 04:10:02','2025-08-30T14:33:01.766Z',NULL);
INSERT INTO "tributes" ("id","name","message","image_url","email","phone","approved","created_at","approved_at","admin_notes") VALUES(114,'Shirley Lo',replace(replace('I may not have been one of the bright students Professor Rhodes would remember, but his presence has left a lasting handprint on my heart. I still remember those early days when I doubted whether I could be a good lawyer or even if I should continue my LLB studies. It was the joy of attending his lectures that made me stay, and the encouragement he gave me during my mid-terms and exams meant more than I could ever express.\r\n\r\nMuch of my time as an LLB student has faded from memory, but his lectures, tutorials, and jokes have stayed with me. I still remember how he taught us Donoghue v Stevenson and other principles of tort law.\r\n\r\nProfessor Rhodes, I hope you know that I now work in the Legal Aid Department, serving the general public every day. I always strive to be a good lawyer, and if the public ever finds value in my work, it is because of you.\r\n\r\nThank you for believing in me before I even believed in myself.\r\n\r\nWith deepest condolences.','\r',char(13)),'\n',char(10)),NULL,'sinyinglo@hotmail.com',NULL,1,'2025-08-30 06:22:42','2025-08-30T14:33:04.518Z',NULL);
INSERT INTO "tributes" ("id","name","message","image_url","email","phone","approved","created_at","approved_at","admin_notes") VALUES(115,'Felicity Ng',replace(replace('I first got to know Peter as a passionate and humorous Tort law professor. Peter always made his lectures lively and easy to understand, he was a dynamic speaker and had the best soundbites to distill complex concepts. Everyone knew better to do their readings and prepare for Peter’s classes, otherwise he would playfully “give you the bullet” for not answering his questions!\r\n\r\nI then came to know Peter as my Vis coach, he was dedicated and intense. Peter liked to say that it was “tough love”, but we all knew it was really just “love”.  He had high standards for us because he truly believed in what we could achieve. He was in the journey with us through every step and through sweat and tears, commenting on every draft we prepared, brainstorming with us during our late night memorial drafting, preparing with us for every practice moot and pre-moot he lined up for us so that we could learn from the best universities and the best lawyers (as our practice arbitrators). “Challenge accepted” was the motto Peter had us bear in mind, and we did rise to every challenge. Peter encouraged us to learn our oral submissions so well that we would “live and breathe” them, he trained every single member of the team to possess the necessary advocacy skills to be an oralist. After every competition round, even if it was late into the night, Peter would sit down with the whole team to debrief and give us constructive comments. Peter motivated us, instilled in us a strong sense of work ethics, and equipped us with the skills and mindset to become a real world practitioner. \r\n\r\nPeter also knew how to have fun. During the Vis competition in Vienna, Peter would also bring us to the most vibrant restaurants, introducing us to the local cuisine - the pork knuckle, schnitzel, sachertorte, and the Almdudler, he showed us around and took us to the Easter markets and made sure we worked hard and played hard. He cultivated a warm, supportive, and long-lasting community - the Vis family, connecting generations of Vis family members through him and Connie’s hospitality.\r\n\r\nI will always be grateful to him for his mentorship and confidence in me, especially the references he kindly wrote for me which enabled me to embark on an LLM at Cambridge on double scholarship. Now in practice, Vis continued to be a part of my career, from a Vis mootie to an arbitration practitioner and an arbitrator in the competitions. In hindsight, I wish I had done better at staying in touch. I had the chance to return to the university as a guest arbitrator and also caught up with him on several occasions and over Zoom, he never seemed to run out of energy and enthusiasm, he continued to be kind, caring, encouraging, and a father figure to his students. He had inspired myself and so many others. Thank you so much again Peter for everything, you are dearly missed.','\r',char(13)),'\n',char(10)),'/api/images/tribute-1756551061450-rpi5802op.jpeg',NULL,NULL,1,'2025-08-30 10:51:02','2025-08-30T14:33:06.793Z',NULL);
INSERT INTO "tributes" ("id","name","message","image_url","email","phone","approved","created_at","approved_at","admin_notes") VALUES(116,'Michael Rhodes',replace(replace('Goodbye my dear brother, Peter,\r\n\r\nI will always miss you.  Never did I think I would not see you again. I was looking forward to your trip to New Zealand this December, as you would be retired and enjoying your retirement, but it is not to be.\r\n\r\nI will miss your many emails and photos documenting all the many places you travelled to. They came with such detailed information, I never needed to look anything up.\r\n\r\nI have many lovely memories of all the travels we did together as children and later as adults. From our trip to New Zealand in 1957, and our Europe trip in 1965 ,with our parents, to our road trip through the USA in 1972 to the wonderful travels through eastern Türkiye and Armenia in 2015, with Connie and Jean. As you would say, our family is always traveling. \r\n\r\nI will miss our frequent video calls about what you and the family were doing and where you were planning to travel to next.\r\n\r\nI will miss you, being the best brother anyone could have wished for.You were always supportive, generous and so family orientated. \r\n \r\nPeter, you will always be in my thoughts.\r\n\r\nRest In Peace, My dearest Brother.','\r',char(13)),'\n',char(10)),'/api/images/tribute-1756636411522-9pa1lobrj.jpeg',NULL,NULL,1,'2025-08-31 10:33:32','2025-08-31T10:35:08.153Z',NULL);
INSERT INTO "tributes" ("id","name","message","image_url","email","phone","approved","created_at","approved_at","admin_notes") VALUES(117,'Ella Leung',replace(replace('I met Peter many years ago at the Chung Chi College English Table, where we had dinner with students on Tuesday nights and helped them practice their conversational skills. Peter would always find time to attend the English Table even after a long day''s work. He was a very kind and patient teacher, and the students loved discussing with him. Thank you, Peter! We will miss you dearly.\r\n','\r',char(13)),'\n',char(10)),'/api/images/tribute-1756644813063-xtuf6unhs.jpeg','ellaleung@cuhk.edu.hk',NULL,1,'2025-08-31 12:53:34','2025-08-31T12:57:07.295Z',NULL);
INSERT INTO "tributes" ("id","name","message","image_url","email","phone","approved","created_at","approved_at","admin_notes") VALUES(118,'Anonymous','In your memorial it''s mentioned multiple times that you believe in us before we believe in ourselves. Yes, Peter, you believed in me much earlier before I believe in myself. Whenever I doubt myself I''ll always think of you fondly.',NULL,NULL,NULL,1,'2025-09-25 16:05:42','2025-09-26T22:18:18.335Z',NULL);
INSERT INTO "tributes" ("id","name","message","image_url","email","phone","approved","created_at","approved_at","admin_notes") VALUES(119,'Anonymous','I only just learned of Professor Rhodes’ passing this past July, and the news has persistently stayed with me. I had the privilege of being among the last cohort of students he taught, something I now hold with deep gratitude. What always puzzled (and inspired) me was how someone of his age could be so tireless, so fully present in every lecture, and so deeply committed to his work. He carried himself not with the weight of his experience, but with a humility that made him approachable and genuinely invested in each of us. He was, in every sense, remarkable, not only for what he knew, but for how he chose to share it. I feel fortunate to have learned from him, even briefly. His influence will remain.',NULL,NULL,NULL,1,'2026-03-22 16:11:20','2026-03-22T20:00:02.908Z',NULL);
INSERT INTO "tributes" ("id","name","message","image_url","email","phone","approved","created_at","approved_at","admin_notes") VALUES(120,'Zlyucnik Petar','Present today we gather in quiet remembrance together of one whose years were spent within these halls. Often described as steady, thoughtful, and quietly composed, remembered for a certain calm and lasting presence. Through lectures that marked the passing academic terms, each class followed a measured and careful course, and many recall those long and patient afternoons. Considering ideas he set before attentive listeners, held within well-ordered notes and structured explanations, echoing familiar lines drawn from established traditions, rarely straying far beyond the written material provided. In time, his name became widely known here. Given a place among respected members of faculty, noted for consistency in both method and demeanor. Often maintaining a certain professional and clear distance, reserved in manner, deliberate and careful in tone, even in moments that might have welcomed warmth. Still, he remained as he always had been. Students passed through his classroom year after year, taking with them what lessons they were able, understanding came in time, though sometimes quite slowly. Days blended together across the span of semester, each lesson resembling closely the one before it. Now we look back with thoughtful and quiet reflection, thinking on what was given within these walls, so we mark his passing with measured words.',NULL,NULL,NULL,1,'2026-04-19 18:29:48','2026-04-20T14:33:37.643Z',NULL);
